1
00:00:52,691 --> 00:00:55,125
<i>1961. The Cold War rages...</i>

2
00:00:55,194 --> 00:00:58,857
<i>between the United States
and the Communist powers.</i>

3
00:00:58,931 --> 00:01:03,391
<i>It is a war of nerves, of threats
and bluffs, of military bluster.</i>

4
00:01:03,468 --> 00:01:06,801
<i>Armies and ominous tanks
line the streets of Moscow...</i>

5
00:01:06,872 --> 00:01:09,238
<i>as do missiles with warheads...</i>

6
00:01:09,308 --> 00:01:11,902
<i>carrying the promise of mass destruction.</i>

7
00:01:11,977 --> 00:01:14,844
<i>It is an era of intrigue and espionage.</i>

8
00:01:14,913 --> 00:01:18,872
<i>Soviet spies are routinely
trapped and sent to prisons.</i>

9
00:01:18,951 --> 00:01:21,385
<i>Or they are exchanged for American spies...</i>

10
00:01:21,453 --> 00:01:24,217
<i>incarcerated behind the Iron Curtain.</i>

11
00:01:24,289 --> 00:01:26,985
<i>Tensions culminate
with the shooting down...</i>

12
00:01:27,059 --> 00:01:30,256
<i>of an American high-altitude
reconnaissance plane...</i>

13
00:01:30,329 --> 00:01:32,695
<i>while a U.N. Ambassador,
Henry Cabot Lodge...</i>

14
00:01:32,764 --> 00:01:38,669
<i>shows a hidden microphone the Reds
disguised in the great seal at an embassy.</i>

15
00:01:38,737 --> 00:01:42,969
<i>Abroad, often in the midst of
bloodthirsty Marxist regimes...</i>

16
00:01:43,041 --> 00:01:45,737
<i>tiny islands of free American territory...</i>

17
00:01:45,811 --> 00:01:49,076
<i>in the person of United States embassies...</i>

18
00:01:49,147 --> 00:01:52,583
<i>carry on round-the-clock efforts
to maintain stable relations...</i>

19
00:01:52,651 --> 00:01:57,088
<i>often against hostile
and aggressive populations.</i>

20
00:01:57,155 --> 00:01:59,749
<i>One slip in the world
of Cold War diplomacy...</i>

21
00:01:59,825 --> 00:02:02,589
<i>could lead instantly to nuclear disaster.</i>

22
00:02:09,668 --> 00:02:11,602
<i>One such free outpost...</i>

23
00:02:11,670 --> 00:02:14,833
<i>deep in Communism's fanatic,
totalitarian underbelly...</i>

24
00:02:14,906 --> 00:02:17,204
<i>is where our story takes place.</i>

25
00:02:17,276 --> 00:02:20,473
<i>Here in a quaint but sturdy mansion
of traditional structure...</i>

26
00:02:20,545 --> 00:02:24,641
<i>a dedicated and disciplined group
of foreign-service workers...</i>

27
00:02:24,716 --> 00:02:27,014
<i>representing
the United States government...</i>

28
00:02:27,085 --> 00:02:30,077
<i>navigate with patience and skill
the treacherous shoals...</i>

29
00:02:30,155 --> 00:02:34,091
<i>of international relations
in the Atomic Age.</i>

30
00:02:34,159 --> 00:02:38,095
<i>It is in this small haven
that negotiations take place...</i>

31
00:02:38,163 --> 00:02:43,294
<i>asylum is given and gracious dinners with
dignitaries from all over the world...</i>

32
00:02:43,368 --> 00:02:47,099
<i>are a part of Uncle Sam's
efforts to coexist.</i>

33
00:02:47,172 --> 00:02:52,007
<i>The embassy is run by U.S. Ambassador
Bradley Dunston Magee...</i>

34
00:02:52,077 --> 00:02:54,011
<i>who is proud to serve his nation...</i>

35
00:02:54,079 --> 00:02:56,809
<i>in this poor and hostile environment.</i>

36
00:02:56,882 --> 00:03:01,182
<i>- Soon it'll be fall in Paris.
- Yes, sir.</i>

37
00:03:01,253 --> 00:03:03,778
<i>I wish we were at
the embassy in Paris too, sir.</i>

38
00:03:05,891 --> 00:03:07,825
Well, don't.

39
00:03:07,893 --> 00:03:11,158
Because this is where the war is going
to be won or lost with the Reds.

40
00:03:11,229 --> 00:03:13,512
They don't need top diplomats
at the Folies-Bergere.

41
00:03:13,525 --> 00:03:14,289
Yes, sir.

42
00:03:14,366 --> 00:03:18,132
I didn't mean to imply that the work
we're doing here is not significant.

43
00:03:18,203 --> 00:03:20,137
We've got a job to do,
and we're going to do it.

44
00:03:20,205 --> 00:03:21,712
And we're going to do it
better than anybody else.

45
00:03:21,725 --> 00:03:22,230
Yes, sir.

46
00:03:22,307 --> 00:03:24,241
Here are those allocations you requested.

47
00:03:24,309 --> 00:03:27,710
<i>In addition to Mr. Burns,
Ambassador Magee is ably abetted...</i>

48
00:03:27,779 --> 00:03:30,839
<i>by Mr. John Kilroy, Yale '49.</i>

49
00:03:30,916 --> 00:03:33,180
<i>And Miss Rosemary Pritchard.</i>

50
00:03:33,251 --> 00:03:37,551
<i>Mr. Kilroy's view of Karl Marx is
rather straightforward and simple...</i>

51
00:03:37,622 --> 00:03:40,182
<i>and reflects that of Mr. John Wayne.</i>

52
00:03:40,258 --> 00:03:42,453
The only good Communist
is a dead Communist.

53
00:03:42,527 --> 00:03:44,586
- They're like Indians.
- Oh!

54
00:03:44,663 --> 00:03:46,597
- Ah!
- God!

55
00:03:46,665 --> 00:03:49,793
See, I told you.
It's the fourth one this year.

56
00:03:49,868 --> 00:03:52,234
They think they're dealing with children.

57
00:03:52,304 --> 00:03:54,534
<i>Also working under Ambassador Magee...</i>

58
00:03:54,606 --> 00:03:57,006
<i>is yet another young career diplomat.</i>

59
00:03:57,075 --> 00:03:59,407
<i>And here our story begins.</i>

60
00:04:00,479 --> 00:04:02,811
<i>Come in.</i>

61
00:04:02,881 --> 00:04:05,975
<i>- You sent for me, sir?
- Sit down.</i>

62
00:04:06,051 --> 00:04:08,281
Yes, sir. Thank you, sir.

63
00:04:08,353 --> 00:04:12,551
<i>Because of my superior record here,
my accomplishments...</i>

64
00:04:12,624 --> 00:04:16,253
the leaders of my party are discussing
the possibility of a cabinet position for me.

65
00:04:16,328 --> 00:04:18,262
Of course, this is all very hush-hush.

66
00:04:18,330 --> 00:04:21,458
<i>Well, sir, let me say I think you'd be
a wonderful asset to the president.</i>

67
00:04:21,533 --> 00:04:26,232
Your broad outlook would appeal to psychotic
liberals as well as militant fascists.

68
00:04:26,304 --> 00:04:28,238
Something for everyone.

69
00:04:28,306 --> 00:04:31,673
<i>Don't mind telling you this would be a crowning
jewel in a lifetime of foreign service.</i>

70
00:04:31,743 --> 00:04:33,677
<i>- Naturally.
- Closing the deal, however...</i>

71
00:04:33,745 --> 00:04:35,940
will take considerable effort on my part.

72
00:04:36,014 --> 00:04:38,744
You know how it is.
The right dinner parties.

73
00:04:38,817 --> 00:04:41,843
Golf course. Calling in a few favors.

74
00:04:41,920 --> 00:04:44,480
Naturally, my presence
in Washington will be essential.

75
00:04:44,556 --> 00:04:46,990
Sir, I understand,
and I won't let you down.

76
00:04:49,127 --> 00:04:51,823
I'm tempted to leave
Mr. Kilroy in charge...

77
00:04:51,897 --> 00:04:53,922
but I don't think that would
look very good image-wise.

78
00:04:53,999 --> 00:04:58,402
Dad... Sir, I realize that my record
at various embassies...

79
00:04:58,470 --> 00:05:01,530
has been less than perfect,
but what can go wrong in two weeks?

80
00:05:01,606 --> 00:05:03,836
You were in Brazil for two weeks,
and you had them importing coffee.

81
00:05:03,909 --> 00:05:07,037
- No, see, that was...
- My own son who I raised to be a diplomat...

82
00:05:07,112 --> 00:05:10,377
- was asked to leave Africa.
- Don't get worked up, Dad.

83
00:05:10,449 --> 00:05:12,610
Some of the best men
in foreign service have...

84
00:05:12,684 --> 00:05:14,652
at one time or another,
been asked to leave a country.

85
00:05:14,719 --> 00:05:18,018
Africa is a continent. You were
recalled from an entire continent.

86
00:05:18,089 --> 00:05:20,057
I'm not really a natural
at it, like you are.

87
00:05:20,125 --> 00:05:22,923
You were hung in effigy in Panama!
Even I didn't know that.

88
00:05:22,994 --> 00:05:23,773
I told you that.

89
00:05:23,786 --> 00:05:26,157
Yes, but you didn't tell me
it was by our own embassy!

90
00:05:26,231 --> 00:05:28,324
Dad, you've been more than tolerant.

91
00:05:28,400 --> 00:05:30,732
- I realize I've had
a hard time finding myself.

92
00:05:30,802 --> 00:05:33,293
Sorry. A little reflux.

93
00:05:33,371 --> 00:05:36,670
If you could just give me this one chance.

94
00:05:36,741 --> 00:05:38,675
- Take this.
- That's glue.

95
00:05:46,718 --> 00:05:48,652
You can trust me, sir.

96
00:05:57,596 --> 00:05:59,530
Mr. Kilroy?

97
00:05:59,598 --> 00:06:03,898
In the ambassador's absence,
I will be in charge here.

98
00:06:03,969 --> 00:06:06,437
Now I realize there's some
discrepancy in our experience...

99
00:06:06,505 --> 00:06:11,033
and I don't want that to cause
any awkwardness or resentment.

100
00:06:11,109 --> 00:06:14,909
I intend to run a disciplined ship,
but a fair one.

101
00:06:14,980 --> 00:06:18,472
Now the word around here is that
you don't really approve of me.

102
00:06:18,550 --> 00:06:20,484
Am I to believe that?

103
00:06:22,921 --> 00:06:24,855
You can speak freely.

104
00:06:24,923 --> 00:06:28,290
I encourage my staff
to honestly express themselves...

105
00:06:28,360 --> 00:06:31,887
<i>in an environment of open frankness.</i>

106
00:06:31,963 --> 00:06:34,022
<i>So, you know, off the record...</i>

107
00:06:34,099 --> 00:06:36,033
<i>what do you think of me?</i>

108
00:06:36,101 --> 00:06:40,265
I think you're a moron. Totally
unsuited to the diplomatic corps.

109
00:06:40,338 --> 00:06:42,738
Unequal to the task of fighting Communism.

110
00:06:42,807 --> 00:06:45,503
Clinging desperately
to a disastrous career...

111
00:06:45,577 --> 00:06:48,011
through the good graces
of your father's connections.

112
00:06:48,079 --> 00:06:50,775
In short, despite
your family's advantages...

113
00:06:50,849 --> 00:06:53,340
a born failure.

114
00:06:53,418 --> 00:06:55,978
Ah. You needn't hide your feelings...

115
00:06:56,054 --> 00:06:57,988
just to spare me.

116
00:06:58,056 --> 00:06:59,990
<i>Will that be all?</i>

117
00:07:00,058 --> 00:07:01,923
Yeah. Yes. Th-Thank you.

118
00:07:01,993 --> 00:07:04,587
Thank you for being so candid.

119
00:07:04,663 --> 00:07:07,029
You know, it's refreshing
when someone despises you...

120
00:07:07,098 --> 00:07:10,192
to hear it phrased so succinctly.

121
00:07:10,268 --> 00:07:13,601
<i>And so Ambassador Magee
departed for the United States...</i>

122
00:07:13,672 --> 00:07:16,698
<i>to pursue the political plum
of a cabinet position...</i>

123
00:07:16,775 --> 00:07:19,209
<i>in the J.F.K. Administration.</i>

124
00:07:19,277 --> 00:07:21,837
<i>And, indeed, the embassy
left in his son's care...</i>

125
00:07:21,913 --> 00:07:24,643
<i>did proceed with business as usual.</i>

126
00:07:26,751 --> 00:07:31,245
<i>A daily operation, well oiled
over time by Ambassador Magee...</i>

127
00:07:31,323 --> 00:07:34,383
<i>functioned almost on automatic pilot.</i>

128
00:07:34,459 --> 00:07:36,689
<i>Visas were handled and renewed.</i>

129
00:07:36,761 --> 00:07:39,195
<i>A complex and detailed
discussion that took place...</i>

130
00:07:39,264 --> 00:07:42,256
<i>on pressing economic matters went well.</i>

131
00:07:42,334 --> 00:07:45,462
<i>There was even a very successful
cocktail reception...</i>

132
00:07:45,537 --> 00:07:48,734
<i>for a highly-placed Italian industrialist.</i>

133
00:07:48,807 --> 00:07:52,402
<i>And then on the fourth day,
from out of nowhere...</i>

134
00:07:52,477 --> 00:07:54,411
<i>- Yes, sir.
- The crisis occurred.</i>

135
00:07:54,479 --> 00:07:58,438
Yes, we are prepared to receive the emir.

136
00:07:58,516 --> 00:08:00,450
Well...

137
00:08:00,518 --> 00:08:03,316
We're giving him the entire third floor.

138
00:08:03,388 --> 00:08:07,085
He's arriving with a few more in
his entourage than we expected, but...

139
00:08:07,158 --> 00:08:10,855
Dad, we converted the library into
a guest bedroom. It just makes it.

140
00:08:10,929 --> 00:08:14,387
<i>I'm sorry, sir.</i>

141
00:08:14,466 --> 00:08:18,163
No, I'm sorry.
I couldn't hear you. There's...

142
00:08:18,236 --> 00:08:21,069
No, if you want to stay a few
more weeks, it's no problem.

143
00:08:21,139 --> 00:08:23,699
<i>Yeah.</i>

144
00:08:23,775 --> 00:08:27,108
They're probably just
shooting one of their poets.

145
00:08:27,178 --> 00:08:29,703
Now, Dad, everything is fine. Sir...

146
00:08:29,781 --> 00:08:32,443
Sir, you can relax. I am carrying the ball.

147
00:08:36,321 --> 00:08:38,619
Okay. Thank you. Bye.

148
00:08:38,690 --> 00:08:40,817
<i>Sir, would you please help us?</i>

149
00:08:44,329 --> 00:08:46,263
We're Americans! Who else
would wear these clothes?

150
00:08:46,331 --> 00:08:49,789
- We're churchpeople.
- Mr. Kilroy!

151
00:08:49,868 --> 00:08:52,029
- Come with me.
- Are you all right?

152
00:08:52,103 --> 00:08:54,148
I'm fine! How could you
tell him we're churchpeople?

153
00:08:54,161 --> 00:08:55,095
You know, good people.

154
00:08:57,242 --> 00:08:59,710
- What the hell is going on?
- They were caught in the act of spying.

155
00:08:59,778 --> 00:09:03,179
Oh, man. Please, please.
You can't come in here. Calm down.

156
00:09:03,248 --> 00:09:06,274
<i>Hand them over to us.
We'll drag them out and shoot them.</i>

157
00:09:06,351 --> 00:09:11,220
This embassy's United States territory.
No one will be dragged out and shot.

158
00:09:11,289 --> 00:09:14,588
Leave the premises at once. This is an
extreme violation of international conduct.

159
00:09:14,659 --> 00:09:17,253
I'm Axel Magee. I'm in charge of this
embassy while the ambassador's away.

160
00:09:17,328 --> 00:09:19,990
Now... I'm gonna have to ask you
to leave immediately.

161
00:09:20,065 --> 00:09:23,159
Guns or no guns, if you don't go,
Mr. Kilroy will throw you out.

162
00:09:23,234 --> 00:09:24,146
<i>Back up!</i>

163
00:09:24,159 --> 00:09:26,931
<i>I think we should issue
a categorical denial...</i>

164
00:09:27,005 --> 00:09:29,906
I don't have the facts. I can't commit
to anything without the facts.

165
00:09:29,974 --> 00:09:33,501
I'm in charge! This will all be settled!

166
00:09:33,578 --> 00:09:36,809
You invade our sanctity with weapons?

167
00:09:36,881 --> 00:09:39,748
You wonder how a brutal
dictatorship gets a bad name.

168
00:09:39,818 --> 00:09:41,752
- Okay, that's enough. Come on.
- That's enough.

169
00:09:43,955 --> 00:09:46,617
You have to deny it!
You can't be indecisive!

170
00:09:46,691 --> 00:09:49,558
I wasn't indecisive.
I just couldn't make a decision.

171
00:09:49,627 --> 00:09:52,061
Our government has a fixed policy
regarding espionage.

172
00:09:52,130 --> 00:09:54,064
Did you tell them we're spies?

173
00:09:54,132 --> 00:09:56,828
Will you stop? He's always eavesdropping.

174
00:09:56,901 --> 00:10:00,997
He didn't deny it. They said
we're spies. They say we're spies.

175
00:10:01,072 --> 00:10:04,269
How can I spy? With my eyesight,
I'm gonna be a spy?

176
00:10:04,342 --> 00:10:07,539
I didn't tell them you were spies. First
rule, Mr. Kilroy, keep your options open.

177
00:10:07,612 --> 00:10:10,046
First no movie on the plane, now this.

178
00:10:10,115 --> 00:10:12,140
This is all just a simple misunderstanding.

179
00:10:12,217 --> 00:10:14,151
Simple? What do you mean, simple?
How simple?

180
00:10:14,219 --> 00:10:16,744
If we leave the building, they shoot us.
Is that simple enough?

181
00:10:16,821 --> 00:10:19,381
First there'd be like a show trial,
then they'd shoot you.

182
00:10:19,457 --> 00:10:22,858
- Who is this guy?
- Perhaps we should notify Ambassador Magee.

183
00:10:22,927 --> 00:10:26,328
- That will not be necessary.
- A man takes his family on a vacation...

184
00:10:26,397 --> 00:10:28,922
and this is what we have
working in our government.

185
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:31,662
- Then they wonder why I don't vote.
- I have done nothing wrong here.

186
00:10:31,736 --> 00:10:32,597
Me neither.

187
00:10:32,610 --> 00:10:35,228
Why did you take pictures?
You knew it was forbidden.

188
00:10:35,306 --> 00:10:37,467
I didn't think they'd see. I have a Minox.

189
00:10:37,542 --> 00:10:41,000
- What did you think when the sirens went off?
- I thought it was lunch break.

190
00:10:41,079 --> 00:10:43,980
- What did you photograph?
- Nothing. The sunset.

191
00:10:44,048 --> 00:10:46,949
If you knew it was a sunset,
how could the sirens be lunch?

192
00:10:47,018 --> 00:10:48,952
Leave me alone because I got a headache.

193
00:10:49,020 --> 00:10:51,784
They're paranoid, and you're
a nudge for the whole trip.

194
00:10:51,856 --> 00:10:55,087
You know, he's right. He is right.
Everything, they hide.

195
00:10:55,160 --> 00:10:57,685
I don't know why
I listen to you in the first place.

196
00:10:57,762 --> 00:11:00,754
Every time I listen to what you say,
I wind up behind the eight ball.

197
00:11:00,832 --> 00:11:03,164
- Here we go again.
- A man has a vacation.

198
00:11:03,234 --> 00:11:06,965
He wants to take his family someplace. I
said we'll get a cabana in Atlantic Beach.

199
00:11:07,038 --> 00:11:09,199
Every year it has to be Atlantic Beach?

200
00:11:09,274 --> 00:11:11,834
To what? Sit in the sun and hear you
complain about over-freckling?

201
00:11:11,910 --> 00:11:14,071
No, this is better. Europe is better.

202
00:11:14,145 --> 00:11:17,080
$6,000 for three weeks
of uninterrupted diarrhea.

203
00:11:17,148 --> 00:11:20,174
What's so terrible? My brother
suggested we see Europe.

204
00:11:20,251 --> 00:11:21,478
He had a wonderful time.

205
00:11:21,491 --> 00:11:24,017
I have to live for her brother.
Do you hear this?

206
00:11:24,088 --> 00:11:26,989
- That's a hot one.
- I know you folks are excited...

207
00:11:27,058 --> 00:11:29,526
- Sorry.
- That's all right. I gotta get a few facts here.

208
00:11:29,594 --> 00:11:33,052
Yes, Mr. And Mrs. Walter Hollander.
Newark, New Jersey.

209
00:11:33,131 --> 00:11:35,565
I'll give you the facts.
The facts are I get a vacation.

210
00:11:35,633 --> 00:11:39,262
I want to take my family someplace.
So I say we'll go to Atlantic Beach.

211
00:11:39,337 --> 00:11:41,737
We'll swim. There's miniature golf.
We can play pinochle.

212
00:11:41,806 --> 00:11:44,502
No! Her brother says go to Europe.
We gotta go to Eur...

213
00:11:44,576 --> 00:11:47,841
And we must... He tells us we must go
behind the Iron Curtain.

214
00:11:47,912 --> 00:11:50,403
Meanwhile, on his vacation,
he went to the French Riviera.

215
00:11:50,481 --> 00:11:52,915
Aren't you interested to see
how the other half lives?

216
00:11:52,984 --> 00:11:55,509
We went with you
to the Crazy Horse in Paris.

217
00:11:55,587 --> 00:11:58,988
A striptease joint. He takes me to
where women get completely naked.

218
00:11:59,057 --> 00:12:01,890
Are you comparing Communism to those girls?

219
00:12:01,960 --> 00:12:03,894
As if he appreciates Europe anyway.

220
00:12:03,962 --> 00:12:05,987
We took him to Westminster Abbey,
his feet hurt.

221
00:12:06,064 --> 00:12:09,227
We took him to Buckingham Palace,
he tried to make the guards laugh.

222
00:12:09,300 --> 00:12:11,359
We took him to the Sistine Chapel,
he never saw the mural.

223
00:12:11,436 --> 00:12:14,462
The mural's on the ceiling.
I can't look up. I get dizzy.

224
00:12:14,539 --> 00:12:17,406
- He had to paint the mural on the ceiling?
- In the Louvre...

225
00:12:17,475 --> 00:12:19,602
I took him to see the statue
of Venus de Milo.

226
00:12:19,677 --> 00:12:22,475
I turn away for one minute,
he's caressing the bosom.

227
00:12:22,547 --> 00:12:24,481
- She cannot take a joke.
- The man is caressing the bosom.

228
00:12:24,549 --> 00:12:27,017
Yes, I felt the statue.
She cannot take a joke.

229
00:12:27,085 --> 00:12:30,179
Have either you ever had any stomach
ailments or respiratory problems?

230
00:12:30,255 --> 00:12:31,223
What is he doing?

231
00:12:31,236 --> 00:12:34,123
I have this brother... You
see, I have this brother.

232
00:12:34,192 --> 00:12:36,319
<i>- He's a wonderful man.
- He's a Nazi.</i>

233
00:12:36,394 --> 00:12:38,885
- Do you know what you're talking about?
- He should be wearing an armband.

234
00:12:38,963 --> 00:12:42,296
- Take my word for it.
- Here we go. "Request for Asylum."

235
00:12:42,367 --> 00:12:46,428
What about asylum? I'm a caterer
from New Jersey. What do I need asylum?

236
00:12:46,504 --> 00:12:49,564
I'm gonna need your passports,
and I gotta get some other information.

237
00:12:49,641 --> 00:12:52,041
I'm giving information.
It began with my brother.

238
00:12:52,110 --> 00:12:55,136
- He's quite a lovely individual.
- They should have hung him at Nuremberg.

239
00:12:55,213 --> 00:12:57,773
"Have you ever bought anything
on credit?" What the hell is this?

240
00:12:57,849 --> 00:12:59,817
What is what l... What are we doing here?

241
00:12:59,884 --> 00:13:03,320
A man goes on a vacation... This is crazy.

242
00:13:03,388 --> 00:13:06,084
- You know, here. Who has the passports?
- That's fine.

243
00:13:06,157 --> 00:13:08,455
Hollander and Blackwell.
I'm a caterer from Newark.

244
00:13:08,526 --> 00:13:11,154
Take my card. You'll find us in...

245
00:13:11,229 --> 00:13:14,562
- Here.
- Great. Do you work, Mrs. Hollander?

246
00:13:14,632 --> 00:13:16,862
No, no, sir. I'm an average housewife.

247
00:13:16,935 --> 00:13:19,267
She's a professional mah-jongg hustler.

248
00:13:19,337 --> 00:13:21,362
She travels around
with her own tiles in a case.

249
00:13:21,439 --> 00:13:24,636
Okay, now, you innocently
snapped some photos? Is that...

250
00:13:24,709 --> 00:13:26,768
Yes, we wandered away from a guided tour.

251
00:13:26,844 --> 00:13:30,336
- His sense of direction is terrible.
- What are you telling him this for?

252
00:13:30,415 --> 00:13:33,646
Will you listen to me, Mr. Magee?
He starts out driving to the Catskills...

253
00:13:33,718 --> 00:13:36,846
- and he winds up in the Adirondacks.
- She has all the answers.

254
00:13:36,921 --> 00:13:39,754
Then they started to chase you, and
you had the good sense to come here.

255
00:13:39,824 --> 00:13:43,351
- My daughter had the presence of mind.
- It's a good thing she did.

256
00:13:43,428 --> 00:13:45,896
So you could tell her we're spies,
'cause you don't deny it.

257
00:13:45,964 --> 00:13:49,525
- I didn't say anything.
- My wife should not have to go through this.

258
00:13:49,600 --> 00:13:53,036
- She's not a young woman.
- What do you mean, I'm an old woman?

259
00:13:53,104 --> 00:13:57,131
I'm not saying old. You're not old,
but she had bridge work recently.

260
00:13:57,208 --> 00:14:00,177
Look, I just don't think
there's anything to worry about.

261
00:14:00,244 --> 00:14:02,212
Sure, 'cause I'm a caterer, not a spy.

262
00:14:02,280 --> 00:14:04,339
Creative catering is our specialty.

263
00:14:04,415 --> 00:14:06,906
We were the first to make
the bridgegroom out of potato salad.

264
00:14:06,985 --> 00:14:08,919
He does lovely work.
I'll have to say that for him.

265
00:14:08,987 --> 00:14:12,582
Last month we did an affair. I made
the bridegroom from potato salad.

266
00:14:12,657 --> 00:14:14,887
The head was a jello mold,
and there was a clam dip...

267
00:14:14,959 --> 00:14:16,893
that we did the rest of the body in.

268
00:14:16,961 --> 00:14:18,588
Fruit punch spouting...

269
00:14:18,663 --> 00:14:20,654
- It was a marvelous affair.
- Beautiful. It was.

270
00:14:20,732 --> 00:14:23,030
I should be able to straighten
this out in a few days.

271
00:14:23,101 --> 00:14:25,569
A few days? What are you, nuts?
I'm not gonna stay here a few days.

272
00:14:25,636 --> 00:14:27,570
We'll have Mr. Burns set up some cots.

273
00:14:27,638 --> 00:14:29,936
Cots! This is getting worse and worse.

274
00:14:30,008 --> 00:14:33,171
I can't sleep on a cot. I'm a dignified
human being with a hernia.

275
00:14:33,244 --> 00:14:36,179
Mr. Hollander, this is an emergency.
We're gonna try the best we can, okay?

276
00:14:36,247 --> 00:14:39,444
No, I can't stay here.
This is the height of the season.

277
00:14:39,517 --> 00:14:41,508
Sam Blackwell can't run
the business without me.

278
00:14:41,586 --> 00:14:43,554
Look, he's a wonderful man.

279
00:14:43,621 --> 00:14:46,681
I have respect for him. He's my partner.
He's a lovely individual...

280
00:14:46,758 --> 00:14:49,056
but the man is a total abject imbecile.

281
00:14:49,127 --> 00:14:51,618
It'll be all right.
Alvin'll come in. His son'll come in.

282
00:14:51,696 --> 00:14:52,608
He's over 21.

283
00:14:52,621 --> 00:14:55,393
Son? Who's gonna dress him?
He's dumber than his father.

284
00:14:55,466 --> 00:14:58,526
- I'm sure the business can wait a couple of days.
- Folks, that's it for me.

285
00:14:58,603 --> 00:15:02,266
I'm sorry if I damaged anything,
but now I'm going to America.

286
00:15:02,340 --> 00:15:04,274
Mr. Magee, what do you
think's gonna happen?

287
00:15:04,342 --> 00:15:07,311
- I'm a caterer. Let 'em capture me.
- This is preposterous.

288
00:15:07,378 --> 00:15:10,506
They want information, I'll tell them
how to make grapefruit sections.

289
00:15:10,581 --> 00:15:13,311
- Mr. Hollander, you can't just go out there.
- You know what? Let him go.

290
00:15:13,384 --> 00:15:16,114
Go ahead, big shot. Listen,
we'll be in here if you want us.

291
00:15:16,187 --> 00:15:18,712
- Go ahead. There's the front door.
- You think I'm afraid to go out?

292
00:15:18,790 --> 00:15:21,725
- I'm afraid...
- No. Why should you be afraid?

293
00:15:21,793 --> 00:15:24,694
They're only police. They'll arrest you,
torture you. What's to be afraid of?

294
00:15:24,762 --> 00:15:27,060
- Yeah, I'm afraid.
- No. Mrs. Hollander...

295
00:15:27,131 --> 00:15:29,224
Go ahead. Go, go. Get brainwashed.

296
00:15:29,300 --> 00:15:31,234
In your case, it'll probably help.

297
00:15:31,302 --> 00:15:33,896
- I urge you not to do anything rash.
- Let him go. Go ahead.

298
00:15:33,971 --> 00:15:36,599
- You don't think I'll go?
- Good-bye! Go!

299
00:15:42,747 --> 00:15:45,011
Do you know if any of those guys
belong to the Masons?

300
00:15:45,083 --> 00:15:47,210
- Ach, you're starting with the Masons.
- The Masons!

301
00:15:47,285 --> 00:15:49,219
<i>- Here they are. Everything's fine.
- Where have you been?</i>

302
00:15:49,287 --> 00:15:52,051
I'm sorry. They had me upstairs.
You wouldn't believe what's outside.

303
00:15:52,123 --> 00:15:54,318
Like 12 armies all with their guns drawn.

304
00:15:54,392 --> 00:15:56,360
- You're all right?
- Yeah, I'm fine, Ma. I'm fine.

305
00:15:56,427 --> 00:15:58,725
Mr. Magee, this is my daughter Susan.

306
00:15:58,796 --> 00:16:01,560
- She was a cesarean.
- Pleased. Axel Magee.

307
00:16:01,632 --> 00:16:04,533
- When will we be free to go home?
- Well, home...

308
00:16:04,602 --> 00:16:07,503
Tell her, tell her. We're liable
to be here two, three days.

309
00:16:07,572 --> 00:16:10,132
- Two, three days? What about Seth?
- Seth?

310
00:16:10,208 --> 00:16:12,142
Seth. Our son Seth. You remem...

311
00:16:12,210 --> 00:16:14,906
Forgive my wife. In her panic, she
forgot that she gave birth twice.

312
00:16:14,979 --> 00:16:17,573
<i>No, no, I-I didn't think
'cause he's at camp.</i>

313
00:16:17,648 --> 00:16:19,616
Camp ends tomorrow.
What are you talking about?

314
00:16:19,684 --> 00:16:21,743
The kid'll be home. He'll be unsupervised.

315
00:16:21,819 --> 00:16:24,344
We're here. He's in the streets.
He'll be running amok.

316
00:16:24,422 --> 00:16:27,585
He'll be raping and looting.
This kid takes after her brother.

317
00:16:27,658 --> 00:16:30,786
<i>Oh, my God. And Susan's
getting married in two weeks.</i>

318
00:16:30,862 --> 00:16:33,057
That's right. I have a deposit
on the hall. Now what?

319
00:16:33,131 --> 00:16:35,565
If we're squeezed for time, we'll
have to push it back. That's what.

320
00:16:35,633 --> 00:16:38,397
The date's been set.
We're not pushing anything.

321
00:16:38,469 --> 00:16:41,165
Maybe she's right. We may
be able to push the date back.

322
00:16:41,239 --> 00:16:45,369
So you better call the owner of
the Renaissance Luau and deal with it.

323
00:16:45,443 --> 00:16:47,377
What are we talking about? Call Donald.

324
00:16:47,445 --> 00:16:50,209
<i>- Tell him that... He'll be worried sick.
- Okay, I'll call Donald.</i>

325
00:16:50,281 --> 00:16:53,045
<i>Mr. Magee, what's the longest
anyone's had to stay here?</i>

326
00:16:53,117 --> 00:16:55,608
Uh, we have a priest
who came to us for asylum.

327
00:16:55,686 --> 00:16:58,348
He's been living upstairs for a while.

328
00:16:58,422 --> 00:17:00,583
What is "a while"?

329
00:17:00,658 --> 00:17:03,491
<i>- A while.
- How long?</i>

330
00:17:03,561 --> 00:17:05,995
Uh, six years.

331
00:17:06,063 --> 00:17:08,122
<i>- Six years.
- Oh, my God.</i>

332
00:17:08,199 --> 00:17:11,362
I said let's go to Atlantic Beach.
We'll swim, we'll play pinochle.

333
00:17:11,435 --> 00:17:13,494
No! Her brother says go to Europe.

334
00:17:13,571 --> 00:17:15,869
<i>- May he rest in peace.
- He's not dead.</i>

335
00:17:15,940 --> 00:17:18,602
He will be as soon as I get back.

336
00:17:23,648 --> 00:17:26,242
<i>I saw it. It was a tiny camera.</i>

337
00:17:26,317 --> 00:17:30,117
I don't understand. Why is there
no electronic surveillance report?

338
00:17:30,188 --> 00:17:33,453
Unfortunately, they must have discovered
the wires. We're getting nothing.

339
00:17:33,524 --> 00:17:35,685
They don't appear to be spies.
They look like a family.

340
00:17:35,760 --> 00:17:40,026
<i>I wouldn't be taken in by appearances.
Note how careful the executive officer was...</i>

341
00:17:40,097 --> 00:17:43,089
to avoid denying any accusation.

342
00:17:43,167 --> 00:17:46,625
Absolutely correct. What puzzles me is...

343
00:17:46,704 --> 00:17:50,572
how he knew to take pictures
at that exact intersection?

344
00:17:50,641 --> 00:17:52,575
<i>There must be spies amongst our own ranks.</i>

345
00:17:52,643 --> 00:17:56,204
I've long suspected people
in our own organization.

346
00:17:56,280 --> 00:17:58,748
Leaks now can prove fatal.

347
00:17:58,816 --> 00:18:02,183
<i>I want the photos and I want Hollanders.</i>

348
00:18:02,253 --> 00:18:05,279
What I'm afraid of is that
before we can move...

349
00:18:05,356 --> 00:18:09,759
they will be used in an exchange
for certain agents the K.G.B. Must...

350
00:18:09,827 --> 00:18:13,456
Once in our possession,
the Hollanders will talk.

351
00:18:13,531 --> 00:18:15,761
And then heads will roll.

352
00:18:26,844 --> 00:18:31,008
So then they shot at Walter,
and we raced down the block.

353
00:18:31,082 --> 00:18:33,016
They're horrible Communists...

354
00:18:33,084 --> 00:18:36,781
with secret police and
those vicious dogs and... God knows.

355
00:18:36,854 --> 00:18:40,187
We may be stuck here for years,
so save the puzzles.

356
00:18:40,258 --> 00:18:42,488
No, it's really a beautiful place, Carol.

357
00:18:42,560 --> 00:18:45,120
They set up these kind
of fold-out beds for us...

358
00:18:45,196 --> 00:18:47,687
in this conference room library.

359
00:18:47,765 --> 00:18:52,134
You'd love Mr. Magee.
He's really very attractive.

360
00:18:52,203 --> 00:18:54,137
I don't know if I miss Donald.

361
00:18:54,205 --> 00:18:56,400
Don't even ask me that question.
Then I get all confused.

362
00:18:56,474 --> 00:18:59,034
The migraines come back.

363
00:18:59,110 --> 00:19:01,044
So how are things in Newark?

364
00:19:01,112 --> 00:19:03,046
Elsie?

365
00:19:03,114 --> 00:19:05,048
Elsie, here's what I want you to do.

366
00:19:05,116 --> 00:19:08,108
I want you to go...
I want you to go into my bedroom...

367
00:19:08,185 --> 00:19:11,120
and look under my pillow.

368
00:19:11,188 --> 00:19:13,850
Look under the pillow. Do you...

369
00:19:13,924 --> 00:19:17,325
There's a small piece of gray flannel.

370
00:19:17,395 --> 00:19:21,161
I want you to take it and wrap it up.
I want you to mail it to me.

371
00:19:21,232 --> 00:19:24,133
Because I'm under tremendous stress...

372
00:19:24,201 --> 00:19:27,967
and I know I'm not gonna be able to
sleep unless I have my piece of flannel.

373
00:19:28,039 --> 00:19:30,166
Yeah, piece of flannel.

374
00:19:30,241 --> 00:19:33,506
Where I suck the tip.

375
00:19:33,577 --> 00:19:37,206
<i>They're taking a very
hard line. Obviously, it's strategic.</i>

376
00:19:37,281 --> 00:19:39,943
<i>What did Washington say?</i>

377
00:19:40,017 --> 00:19:43,316
Well, the truth is, I haven't
contacted the home office yet.

378
00:19:43,387 --> 00:19:46,982
- A formal complaint is in order.
- We have time, Mr. Kilroy.

379
00:19:47,058 --> 00:19:49,322
Then I strongly suggest we cancel
plans to host the emir.

380
00:19:49,393 --> 00:19:51,327
Our Arab friends can be unpredictable.

381
00:19:51,395 --> 00:19:53,386
I think it would be an extreme loss
of face for the emir...

382
00:19:53,464 --> 00:19:56,627
if he were suddenly not permitted
to be our country's guest.

383
00:19:56,701 --> 00:20:00,296
It's a question of space. The emir
will take up the whole third floor.

384
00:20:00,371 --> 00:20:03,306
- Oh. I'm sorry.
- No. Hi. Come in.

385
00:20:03,374 --> 00:20:06,036
- Are you sure? 'Cause...
- Yeah.

386
00:20:06,110 --> 00:20:08,943
Mr. Kilroy, we can...
We'll work this out later.

387
00:20:09,013 --> 00:20:11,811
As you wish.

388
00:20:11,882 --> 00:20:14,783
- Am I interrupting? I can come back.
- No, it's fine.

389
00:20:14,852 --> 00:20:16,888
'Cause I don't want to take
up too much of your time.

390
00:20:16,901 --> 00:20:17,582
No problem.

391
00:20:17,655 --> 00:20:21,147
I just wanted to thank you for the
accommodations. Everyone's been really nice.

392
00:20:21,225 --> 00:20:21,970
Oh, good.

393
00:20:21,983 --> 00:20:24,251
It's a lovely place to be
under the right circumstances.

394
00:20:24,328 --> 00:20:26,311
We'll try to get you out
of here as soon as we can.

395
00:20:26,324 --> 00:20:27,320
We really appreciate it.

396
00:20:27,398 --> 00:20:30,231
- Your dad is really anxious.
- My da... Oh.

397
00:20:30,301 --> 00:20:33,099
No, he's like that all the time.
My parents...

398
00:20:33,170 --> 00:20:35,661
Well, they're not like that
all the time. I mean...

399
00:20:35,740 --> 00:20:39,437
they kind of have a funny way
of communicating with each other.

400
00:20:39,510 --> 00:20:42,274
Deep down, they're affectionate.
They really like each other...

401
00:20:42,346 --> 00:20:46,248
but, I don't know, what you see
is what I envision the Huns to be.

402
00:20:47,518 --> 00:20:50,078
Yeah, well, you know,
it's gotta be hard for them.

403
00:20:50,154 --> 00:20:52,088
Oh, would you like something to drink?

404
00:20:52,156 --> 00:20:55,648
We've got a local white wine. It's, uh...

405
00:20:55,726 --> 00:20:58,126
light, but kind of sneaks up on you.

406
00:20:58,195 --> 00:21:00,459
Oh, I could use something serious.
Thank you.

407
00:21:02,733 --> 00:21:04,667
So...

408
00:21:07,037 --> 00:21:09,130
What do you do?

409
00:21:09,206 --> 00:21:12,733
Uh, not a lot. I majored
in philosophy at Rutgers...

410
00:21:12,810 --> 00:21:16,871
and now I don't feel equipped
to do much of anything...

411
00:21:16,947 --> 00:21:19,677
except think about
the universe, which I do.

412
00:21:19,750 --> 00:21:23,413
I don't know. I could open
a philosophy shop and sell concepts.

413
00:21:26,524 --> 00:21:28,458
- So what do you think about...
- What do I think?

414
00:21:28,526 --> 00:21:31,051
- About the universe.
- Oh, um...

415
00:21:31,128 --> 00:21:34,427
Well, I think it's a,
you know, rough place to be...

416
00:21:34,498 --> 00:21:36,898
unless, of course, you
have someone to share it with.

417
00:21:36,967 --> 00:21:39,333
That makes it easier.

418
00:21:39,403 --> 00:21:43,464
- Fortunately, you do.
- Yes, I do. I hope you do too.

419
00:21:43,541 --> 00:21:46,510
Well, I travel a lot.
Suddenly and unexpectedly.

420
00:21:46,577 --> 00:21:49,410
It must be exciting, you know,
to be in all those different countries.

421
00:21:49,480 --> 00:21:52,608
Mr. Kilroy said you've been in almost
every embassy. That's really amazing.

422
00:21:52,683 --> 00:21:55,015
He said that? Well, not every embassy.

423
00:21:55,085 --> 00:21:57,019
It doesn't sneak up on you,
it just attacks.

424
00:21:57,087 --> 00:21:58,154
You haven't eaten, right?

425
00:21:58,167 --> 00:22:00,284
Look how quickly I'm
talking personally with you.

426
00:22:00,357 --> 00:22:02,587
<i>- I don't like to be forward.
- Don't be silly.</i>

427
00:22:02,660 --> 00:22:05,128
Wine or no wine,
I promise, no more questions.

428
00:22:05,196 --> 00:22:07,664
<i>- What school did you go to?
- Harvard.</i>

429
00:22:07,731 --> 00:22:11,599
<i>I wanted to go to art school,
but my family had other plans.</i>

430
00:22:11,669 --> 00:22:13,603
Oh. That's too bad.

431
00:22:13,671 --> 00:22:16,697
What does your fiancee do?

432
00:22:16,774 --> 00:22:20,175
Um, I don't...
I don't have a fiancee. You do.

433
00:22:20,244 --> 00:22:23,236
Oh! That's right.
Look at me. I'm drunk already.

434
00:22:23,314 --> 00:22:26,249
- Notice I'm not asking you questions.
- That's all right.

435
00:22:29,053 --> 00:22:31,715
- So what does he do? Your fiance.
- Oh, Donald.

436
00:22:31,789 --> 00:22:34,724
He's a dermatologist.
We met at Trader Vic's.

437
00:22:34,792 --> 00:22:38,819
I was choking on some cosmo tidbits.
It's actually an interesting story.

438
00:22:38,896 --> 00:22:41,831
He reached down my throat
and pulled out a toothpick...

439
00:22:41,899 --> 00:22:43,833
with a half-eaten shrimp on the end of it.

440
00:22:43,901 --> 00:22:46,392
- Huh.
- Later that night, we made love.

441
00:22:48,672 --> 00:22:51,732
Beverly, you heard?

442
00:22:51,809 --> 00:22:55,006
Oh, no, no. It's a lovely place.

443
00:22:55,079 --> 00:22:58,071
But if you ask me, whoever
dusts doesn't do a good job.

444
00:22:58,148 --> 00:23:01,982
<i>Leave me alone, please. I don't like
European food. I never liked it.</i>

445
00:23:02,052 --> 00:23:04,247
<i>- So I'm a Philistine.
- Do we have a problem here?</i>

446
00:23:04,321 --> 00:23:06,255
Every dish I name, he says no.

447
00:23:06,323 --> 00:23:08,689
Mr. Hollander, if you have any
special request, I'm sure Oscar...

448
00:23:08,759 --> 00:23:10,852
We are 4,000 miles from the United States.

449
00:23:10,928 --> 00:23:14,557
It's a Communist country. It's 8:00
at night. I can't get lean brisket!

450
00:23:14,632 --> 00:23:16,896
- Fish! What about fish?
- Octopus.

451
00:23:16,967 --> 00:23:19,026
No, not octopus. Not monsters.

452
00:23:19,103 --> 00:23:22,834
- I mean fish, regular fish.
- Oysters, lovely oysters.

453
00:23:22,907 --> 00:23:25,341
Oysters are alive. I don't eat live food.

454
00:23:25,409 --> 00:23:28,401
I want my food dead.
Not sick, not wounded. Dead.

455
00:23:28,479 --> 00:23:30,709
<i>The jellied calf's foot.</i>

456
00:23:30,781 --> 00:23:33,614
<i>Marion, you hear this? He wants me
to eat a jellied calf's foot.</i>

457
00:23:33,684 --> 00:23:37,017
Because of where we are and who we
entertain, our menu can be a little exotic.

458
00:23:37,087 --> 00:23:39,954
So plain boiled chicken.
Is that so complicated?

459
00:23:40,024 --> 00:23:42,219
<i>Usually he has a very nice appetite.</i>

460
00:23:42,293 --> 00:23:44,227
Look how I can't get a meal here.

461
00:23:44,295 --> 00:23:46,229
I'll come in the kitchen.
I'll make you something.

462
00:23:46,297 --> 00:23:48,288
<i>- In my kitchen?
- Don't worry. I know...</i>

463
00:23:48,365 --> 00:23:51,300
Not in my kitchen. No one
works in my kitchen except me.

464
00:23:51,368 --> 00:23:53,859
The cutlery... I have everything just so.

465
00:23:53,938 --> 00:23:56,463
My spice rack. You'll mix up
the order of my spice rack.

466
00:23:56,540 --> 00:23:59,338
I'm getting dizzy. The blinding
headaches are returning.

467
00:23:59,410 --> 00:24:01,776
<i>- I need some water! Cold water!
- Marion.</i>

468
00:24:01,845 --> 00:24:05,406
It's good to know our food is
being cooked by an outpatient.

469
00:24:05,482 --> 00:24:07,814
I spoke to Barney Silverman on the phone.

470
00:24:07,885 --> 00:24:10,080
Did you tell him not to bother
to come to Idyllwild Airport...

471
00:24:10,154 --> 00:24:13,055
with the station wagon
because we may be six years late?

472
00:24:13,123 --> 00:24:15,318
Mrs. Hollander, I meant to speak
to you about the telephone.

473
00:24:15,392 --> 00:24:18,190
You're free to use the phone as much as you'd
like, but if you could limit the calls...

474
00:24:18,262 --> 00:24:20,457
This is nothing for her. Let me tell you.

475
00:24:20,531 --> 00:24:24,592
She's got to alert everyone in Newark
individually like Paul Revere.

476
00:24:24,668 --> 00:24:28,104
I called the Kleins. They're gonna
take care of Seth till we get back.

477
00:24:28,172 --> 00:24:30,697
The Kleins?
You couldn't pick a worse couple.

478
00:24:30,774 --> 00:24:33,436
- Why? What's wrong with the Kleins?
- They have orgies.

479
00:24:33,510 --> 00:24:36,741
- How do you know?
- I catered one. Terrible. These are terrible.

480
00:24:37,381 --> 00:24:38,973
Hey, Ma, Dad, guess who I found upstairs.

481
00:24:39,049 --> 00:24:40,983
Father Drobney, what brings you down here?

482
00:24:41,051 --> 00:24:44,077
I heard such a commotion today, and
I met this lovely young lady upstairs.

483
00:24:44,154 --> 00:24:46,281
These are the Hollanders,
Father Drobney. They came to us today...

484
00:24:46,357 --> 00:24:48,552
under much the same circumstances
you did six years ago.

485
00:24:48,626 --> 00:24:52,323
- Oh, you're refugees.
- Refugees? You know what I paid for this shirt?

486
00:24:52,396 --> 00:24:55,365
<i>- We were at the Vatican. We saw your boss.</i>

487
00:24:55,432 --> 00:24:58,128
- Excuse me.
- He's got this tiny little room on the top floor.

488
00:24:58,202 --> 00:25:01,501
- If it's for me...
- So, what, you don't go crazy up there?

489
00:25:01,572 --> 00:25:04,040
Mm, I'm a guest through
the courtesy of your government.

490
00:25:04,108 --> 00:25:06,133
I do not wish to make myself a nuisance.

491
00:25:06,210 --> 00:25:07,264
Can't you leave here?

492
00:25:07,277 --> 00:25:10,010
Only if there's some drastic
change in national policy.

493
00:25:10,080 --> 00:25:12,105
I have friends who could help me escape...

494
00:25:12,182 --> 00:25:16,846
but I feel it is my duty to return and
someday lead my people once again.

495
00:25:16,920 --> 00:25:19,548
But until you lead your people,
you stay in your bedroom?

496
00:25:19,623 --> 00:25:23,957
Over the years I have developed a hobby,
and so it passes the lonely moments.

497
00:25:24,028 --> 00:25:25,962
<i>- What do you do?
- Father Drobney's a magician.</i>

498
00:25:26,030 --> 00:25:28,965
<i>- I've been practicing for years. Years!
- That's a wonderful hobby.</i>

499
00:25:29,033 --> 00:25:31,866
Okay, pick a card, any card.

500
00:25:31,935 --> 00:25:34,460
Don't show me, show your brains.
Let's go. Pick a card.

501
00:25:34,538 --> 00:25:36,529
I'm not forcing. Here we go.

502
00:25:36,607 --> 00:25:38,666
Anybody pick a card. Okay.

503
00:25:38,742 --> 00:25:41,006
How about you, sir? How about you,
ma'am? Pick a card.

504
00:25:41,078 --> 00:25:43,205
- I'm gonna pick a card.
- Don't matter to me.

505
00:25:43,280 --> 00:25:46,681
Show your brains. Okay.
Place the card in the deck.

506
00:25:46,750 --> 00:25:51,449
Okay, one. Your card is...
the three of diamonds!

507
00:25:51,522 --> 00:25:53,456
- Five of hearts.
- Aha! Aha!

508
00:25:53,524 --> 00:25:54,121
So sorry.

509
00:25:54,134 --> 00:25:55,958
Father Drobney has all sorts
of interesting things up there.

510
00:25:56,026 --> 00:25:58,324
- Don't you, Father?
- Doves. Ooh, I have white doves.

511
00:25:58,395 --> 00:26:01,023
I raise them. I transform them
before your very eyes.

512
00:26:01,098 --> 00:26:03,396
Bring some of your things down.
I think we'd all like to see them.

513
00:26:03,467 --> 00:26:05,401
<i>- Ja! Ooh!
- For entertainment.</i>

514
00:26:05,469 --> 00:26:07,403
<i>- We would. Yes. Wouldn't we, Walter?
- Would you really?</i>

515
00:26:07,471 --> 00:26:09,769
Sure. Why do you think I had us
trapped here? So we could watch him.

516
00:26:09,840 --> 00:26:11,967
I'll be right back.
An audience! An audience!

517
00:26:12,042 --> 00:26:15,500
I'll do rings, the disappearing
handkerchief. Ooh!

518
00:26:15,579 --> 00:26:17,547
And my magic billiard balls!

519
00:26:17,614 --> 00:26:20,139
<i>Terrific. It's The Ed Sullivan Show.</i>

520
00:26:20,217 --> 00:26:22,344
Don't go. I'll be right back. Please stay.

521
00:26:22,419 --> 00:26:25,752
<i>Don't worry. You can count on it.
We'll be here when you get downstairs.</i>

522
00:26:25,823 --> 00:26:28,291
Imagine staying in your room
and practicing magic for six years.

523
00:26:28,358 --> 00:26:29,313
<i>You'd go crazy.</i>

524
00:26:29,326 --> 00:26:32,226
<i>What about us? What if the
same thing happens to us?</i>

525
00:26:32,296 --> 00:26:35,629
Why do you compare?
We're innocent tourists. He's a priest.

526
00:26:35,699 --> 00:26:37,792
I'm sure he could get out of here
if he made some effort...

527
00:26:37,868 --> 00:26:39,802
but you know how it is with those guys.

528
00:26:39,870 --> 00:26:41,838
The one who suffers most
gets the promotion.

529
00:26:41,905 --> 00:26:44,470
<i>Okay. We've managed to retrieve
the luggage from the hotel.</i>

530
00:26:44,483 --> 00:26:45,341
<i>Wonderful.</i>

531
00:26:45,409 --> 00:26:47,343
- It was 19 pieces?
- Yes, thank you.

532
00:26:47,411 --> 00:26:50,778
Mr. Hollander, I think we've solved your
dinner problem. The chef is making you hare.

533
00:26:50,848 --> 00:26:53,373
What's "hair"?

534
00:26:53,450 --> 00:26:55,384
<i>- Hare.
- What's "hair"?</i>

535
00:26:55,452 --> 00:26:57,386
Hare's rabbit, Dad. Hare. Rabbit.

536
00:26:57,454 --> 00:27:00,321
<i>- Pardon? What do you mean?
- It's a rabbit.</i>

537
00:27:00,390 --> 00:27:03,018
<i>It's the closest thing
to chicken the chef could find.</i>

538
00:27:03,093 --> 00:27:05,027
- Bunny rabbit?
- It's delicious.

539
00:27:05,095 --> 00:27:07,359
If you don't ask him, he'll eat
whatever you put in front of him.

540
00:27:07,431 --> 00:27:09,365
Rabbit, like Peter Rabbit, right? Rabbit?

541
00:27:09,433 --> 00:27:11,697
If I told you it was a chicken,
you wouldn't know the difference.

542
00:27:11,769 --> 00:27:15,170
I'm gonna eat a furry object?
What's wrong with you, Marion?

543
00:27:15,239 --> 00:27:17,867
There's not a Chinese restaurant
here we can order out?

544
00:27:17,941 --> 00:27:19,875
<i>- I'm back!
- Oh! He's back.</i>

545
00:27:19,943 --> 00:27:22,776
I could only carry the small items, but...

546
00:27:22,846 --> 00:27:25,713
it's enough for
the first few hours of the show.

547
00:27:25,783 --> 00:27:28,343
<i>How many hours does the show last?</i>

548
00:27:28,418 --> 00:27:31,387
<i>- Ha, ha!
- I can't believe this.</i>

549
00:27:31,455 --> 00:27:34,253
Take this, please. Okay!

550
00:27:36,326 --> 00:27:39,056
I have dreamed of this moment for years.

551
00:27:39,129 --> 00:27:41,495
What miracle shall I start with?

552
00:27:41,565 --> 00:27:43,795
I don't know. Can you walk on water?

553
00:27:43,867 --> 00:27:48,167
Okay. Watch this.

554
00:27:51,074 --> 00:27:53,008
Oh.

555
00:27:55,712 --> 00:27:58,772
Ladies and gentlemen. Nothing up my robes.

556
00:27:58,849 --> 00:28:02,751
- Wonderful, Walter. A tricky priest.
- Great.

557
00:28:02,820 --> 00:28:06,620
Nothing... in my cylinder.

558
00:28:06,690 --> 00:28:08,817
Nothing in my cage.

559
00:28:08,892 --> 00:28:12,191
Okay. Please watch carefully.

560
00:28:13,697 --> 00:28:16,393
<i>I don't need a vaudeville
show. I need a sandwich.</i>

561
00:28:16,466 --> 00:28:20,527
I place this dove inside the cylinder...

562
00:28:20,604 --> 00:28:23,937
and say a few magic words.

563
00:28:24,007 --> 00:28:28,444
<i>And... where there was
previously a dove, is miraculously...</i>

564
00:28:28,512 --> 00:28:31,242
Where's my rabbit? I had a rabbit.

565
00:28:31,315 --> 00:28:33,806
How do you like it?
Rare, medium, well-done?

566
00:28:33,884 --> 00:28:35,818
<i>Hey, that's my rabbit!</i>

567
00:28:35,886 --> 00:28:38,081
You! You assassin!

568
00:28:38,155 --> 00:28:41,249
<i>- Come back here!
- Stop! Stop this now!</i>

569
00:28:41,325 --> 00:28:46,126
This is a United States embassy,
and I intend to run it like one!

570
00:28:48,198 --> 00:28:50,564
- Your bird.
- Take the bird! Take the bird!

571
00:28:50,634 --> 00:28:55,128
<i>Days pass, and
the situation remains unchanged.</i>

572
00:28:55,205 --> 00:28:59,699
<i>And as the crisis reaches the end of
week two, nerves have become frazzled.</i>

573
00:28:59,776 --> 00:29:02,074
- Oh, you could do better, Frank.
- What?

574
00:29:02,145 --> 00:29:04,409
And the second floor needs waxing again.

575
00:29:04,481 --> 00:29:07,348
- We did wax.
- I like it shiny. I'll show you how.

576
00:29:07,417 --> 00:29:10,682
<i>Mrs. Hollander, will you please
remove this ironing board?</i>

577
00:29:10,754 --> 00:29:15,020
<i>Where should I go? If I go into
the kitchen, the chef starts to cry.</i>

578
00:29:15,092 --> 00:29:18,584
Dear Seth.

579
00:29:18,662 --> 00:29:23,065
Don't forget to wash...

580
00:29:23,133 --> 00:29:26,500
behind your neck...

581
00:29:26,570 --> 00:29:29,505
and ears.

582
00:29:29,573 --> 00:29:31,507
Here...

583
00:29:31,575 --> 00:29:35,739
all goes okay.

584
00:29:35,812 --> 00:29:38,178
Last night...

585
00:29:38,248 --> 00:29:42,048
for the first time in my life...

586
00:29:42,119 --> 00:29:45,987
I ate sweetbreads.

587
00:29:46,056 --> 00:29:47,990
Also...

588
00:29:48,058 --> 00:29:51,186
<i>For the first time in my life...</i>

589
00:29:51,261 --> 00:29:56,062
I threw up on an antique carpet.

590
00:29:56,133 --> 00:29:58,328
We all miss you.

591
00:29:58,402 --> 00:30:01,132
<i>Overseas phone call for you, Mr. Hollander.</i>

592
00:30:01,204 --> 00:30:03,138
- Well, good.
- Mrs. Hollander.

593
00:30:03,206 --> 00:30:07,267
You're using the phone. Mr. Hollander's on
the phone. Susan is talking with Donald.

594
00:30:07,344 --> 00:30:10,609
All the incoming lines are
lit up with relatives calling.

595
00:30:10,681 --> 00:30:13,377
Uncle Saul, Minna, the Chomsky twins.

596
00:30:13,450 --> 00:30:15,577
This embassy needs open lines.

597
00:30:15,652 --> 00:30:19,247
Sweetheart, could you put your mother
on for just one minute?

598
00:30:45,515 --> 00:30:49,110
Try and find out, and I'll call you back
in an hour. Love you. Thank you.

599
00:30:49,186 --> 00:30:51,154
<i>Sam Blackwell caters a sweet-sixteen
party. Listen to this.</i>

600
00:30:51,221 --> 00:30:53,781
I don't want to hear about this.

601
00:30:53,857 --> 00:30:56,325
- Tries to give a bargain on the meats.
- I'm not interested.

602
00:30:56,393 --> 00:30:58,732
He tries to buy cheap.
Doesn't use our regular guy.

603
00:30:58,745 --> 00:30:59,658
I'm not listening.

604
00:30:59,730 --> 00:31:03,257
The result is four people go home from
the party, they get food poisoning.

605
00:31:03,333 --> 00:31:04,194
Oh, my God.

606
00:31:04,207 --> 00:31:06,825
They're in the hospital 'cause
this guy looked to buy cheap.

607
00:31:06,903 --> 00:31:08,837
- I'll bet they're suing.
- Aha! Now you're interested.

608
00:31:08,905 --> 00:31:10,839
- Who are they?
- No, you don't want to hear.

609
00:31:10,907 --> 00:31:13,171
- Come on. Tell me.
- No! I'm not gonna say anything.

610
00:31:13,243 --> 00:31:15,177
- You weren't interested.
- All right, I'm not interested.

611
00:31:15,245 --> 00:31:17,338
You're not interested.
Why should I tell you?

612
00:31:17,414 --> 00:31:20,941
- Grouch. Will you answer me?
- No! You didn't want to know anything.

613
00:31:21,018 --> 00:31:22,952
Now I want to know. Tell me. Are they?

614
00:31:23,020 --> 00:31:24,954
Are they suing? No, they're not suing.

615
00:31:25,022 --> 00:31:27,109
We're suing them for low
resistance to tainted meat.

616
00:31:27,122 --> 00:31:27,820
Walter!

617
00:31:27,891 --> 00:31:30,883
Of course they're suing! What do
you expect from poisoned people?

618
00:31:30,961 --> 00:31:32,024
Oh, my God.

619
00:31:32,037 --> 00:31:35,261
If I had Sam Blackwell here,
I would crush his head.

620
00:31:35,332 --> 00:31:37,266
Be thankful nobody died.

621
00:31:37,334 --> 00:31:39,768
Good, Marion. We're thinking
of making that our slogan.

622
00:31:42,305 --> 00:31:44,239
<i>- Hello?
- Got such a heartburn.</i>

623
00:31:44,307 --> 00:31:46,241
Yes. What? No.

624
00:31:46,309 --> 00:31:49,278
Uh, yeah. Hold it. It's New Jersey. Sam.

625
00:31:49,346 --> 00:31:51,337
You be nice. We all make mistakes.

626
00:31:51,415 --> 00:31:53,576
Hello? Hello, cretin?

627
00:31:53,650 --> 00:31:57,347
Hello, cretin?
Poison any more people, cretin?

628
00:31:58,989 --> 00:32:02,015
Four more people went.
They're dropping like flies.

629
00:32:02,092 --> 00:32:05,027
Uh-huh. So what's happening?
What did he say?

630
00:32:05,095 --> 00:32:07,120
Uh... Yeah. Good, good.

631
00:32:07,197 --> 00:32:09,995
The lawyer thinks they have a case.

632
00:32:10,067 --> 00:32:12,194
Uh-huh. Murderer! Murderer!

633
00:32:12,269 --> 00:32:14,362
When l... Oh. I can't hear you.

634
00:32:14,438 --> 00:32:16,906
Your voice is fading, murderer.

635
00:32:16,973 --> 00:32:19,669
Overseas operator,
I can't hear the murderer.

636
00:32:19,743 --> 00:32:23,304
I... Blackwell. Blackwell,
you're finished. You're finished.

637
00:32:23,380 --> 00:32:26,474
When I come home, I'm gonna
rent a car and run you over.

638
00:32:26,550 --> 00:32:30,850
You'll never cater again.
You've cut your last melon ball.

639
00:32:30,921 --> 00:32:32,855
His Majesty has arrived.

640
00:32:32,923 --> 00:32:35,687
Oh, my God... Allah. Uh...

641
00:32:35,759 --> 00:32:37,989
Mr. Magee. Mr. Magee!

642
00:32:38,061 --> 00:32:40,188
<i>Don't call me. I've got problems of my own.</i>

643
00:32:40,263 --> 00:32:43,721
No. If you're gonna call,
call me with good news.

644
00:32:43,800 --> 00:32:46,325
No... Black... Oh, my...

645
00:32:46,403 --> 00:32:49,270
Blackwell, I'll call you later.

646
00:32:49,339 --> 00:32:51,273
<i>What is this? Lawrence of Arabia?</i>

647
00:32:51,341 --> 00:32:53,741
- How do you do, Your Highness?
- "Your Highness"?

648
00:32:53,810 --> 00:32:54,498
You know this guy?

649
00:32:54,511 --> 00:32:56,574
What are you talking about?
He's some kind of a sultan.

650
00:32:56,646 --> 00:32:59,114
His Majesty wishes to thank
his American friends...

651
00:32:59,182 --> 00:33:01,912
for much recent generosity
and understanding.

652
00:33:01,985 --> 00:33:04,613
I am aide to His Majesty and his wives.

653
00:33:04,688 --> 00:33:07,851
- Wives. This bunch here is the wives?
- How do you do? How do you do?

654
00:33:07,924 --> 00:33:11,485
- Can I take your veils?
- I'm Walter Hollander from New Jersey.

655
00:33:11,561 --> 00:33:13,495
Our flight was a rather rough one.

656
00:33:13,563 --> 00:33:16,726
I hope you didn't have any problem
getting past all those police outside.

657
00:33:16,800 --> 00:33:19,030
Walter and I are wanted.

658
00:33:19,102 --> 00:33:22,367
I recogn... This guy I recog...
The newspapers...

659
00:33:22,439 --> 00:33:24,373
Didn't you people
have an uprising recently?

660
00:33:24,441 --> 00:33:26,705
I understand the ambassador
has made arrangements.

661
00:33:26,776 --> 00:33:29,210
I'm right. All those workers got...

662
00:33:29,279 --> 00:33:31,213
- There...
- All those workers got killed.

663
00:33:31,281 --> 00:33:33,272
There are two sides
to that affair, my friend.

664
00:33:33,350 --> 00:33:35,978
What are you talking about, Walter?
Something you know nothing about?

665
00:33:36,052 --> 00:33:38,680
What are you telling me?
I don't know politics?

