896
00:45:52,463 --> 00:45:54,580
We came to say good-bye
and to wish you good luck.

897
00:45:54,657 --> 00:45:57,888
- It's a pity you're leaving.
- Well, look, if you ever need a job...

898
00:45:57,960 --> 00:46:00,861
I know a lot of people in New Jersey
who'd appreciate your kind of cooking.

899
00:46:00,930 --> 00:46:03,592
And don't worry about the Board of
Health, 'cause they'll never catch you.

900
00:46:03,666 --> 00:46:06,931
I may as well tell you, Mr. Hollander,
that the veal you had last night...

901
00:46:07,003 --> 00:46:09,995
was eel, and you cleaned your plate.

902
00:46:10,072 --> 00:46:13,599
Look in the vase
next to the dining room table.

903
00:46:13,676 --> 00:46:17,077
God bless you.
You have made my life richer.

904
00:46:17,146 --> 00:46:20,309
Pick a card.

905
00:46:20,383 --> 00:46:23,284
- Eight of diamonds.
- Look! They're all eight of diamonds!

906
00:46:23,352 --> 00:46:25,286
- So, of course, he gets it.
- Sue me.

907
00:46:25,354 --> 00:46:28,050
I think it's wonderful, Father,
that a man of the cloth...

908
00:46:28,124 --> 00:46:30,092
has a hobby besides just God.

909
00:46:32,728 --> 00:46:35,356
The exchange is a rather
complex one, Mr. Kilroy.

910
00:46:35,431 --> 00:46:37,490
Well, I appreciate your cooperation.

911
00:46:37,566 --> 00:46:40,000
I've contacted the Soviet embassy,
and as you know...

912
00:46:40,069 --> 00:46:43,630
they have a particular interest in the
return of Martin Tolchin as well as Pinchuk.

913
00:46:43,706 --> 00:46:45,731
- Right.
- I'll see you in a minute, Burns.

914
00:46:45,808 --> 00:46:47,935
Marion, look who's here. It's your friend.

915
00:46:48,010 --> 00:46:50,535
I don't hold a grudge.
I'm just happy we're getting out.

916
00:46:50,613 --> 00:46:53,411
I'm... If you ask me,
the whole Cold War stinks, anyhow.

917
00:46:53,482 --> 00:46:55,387
His grandparents were Russian.
They loved Russia.

918
00:46:55,400 --> 00:46:56,542
That's right. They loved it.

919
00:46:56,619 --> 00:46:59,019
They only got out because they heard
there was gonna be a pogrom...

920
00:46:59,088 --> 00:47:01,056
and they had just purchased new dishes.

921
00:47:01,123 --> 00:47:05,287
- Let bygones be bygones.
- If I could have my way...

922
00:47:05,361 --> 00:47:07,329
<i>you and all those like you...</i>

923
00:47:07,396 --> 00:47:09,762
would hang in the public square...

924
00:47:09,832 --> 00:47:12,960
as an example to all
the enemies of the state.

925
00:47:13,035 --> 00:47:15,230
Say, listen, mister,
when was the last time...

926
00:47:15,304 --> 00:47:17,363
you propositioned a woman and she said yes?

927
00:47:17,440 --> 00:47:20,603
You will be jointly
accompanied to the airport...

928
00:47:20,676 --> 00:47:22,610
and safely put on the plane.

929
00:47:22,678 --> 00:47:25,738
Well, here. Take my phone number
in New Jersey.

930
00:47:25,815 --> 00:47:29,182
If you ever decide to defect, call me
'cause we can always use busboys.

931
00:47:29,251 --> 00:47:31,845
<i>Mr. Krojack, you have a telephone call.</i>

932
00:47:31,921 --> 00:47:35,880
The trade is off. Tolchin's a suicide.

933
00:47:35,958 --> 00:47:38,119
Wait. Do they know that here?

934
00:47:41,931 --> 00:47:44,126
If the Hollanders have left
the building, get 'em back.

935
00:47:44,200 --> 00:47:47,226
Quickly. And don't create suspicion.

936
00:47:47,303 --> 00:47:49,965
Ah!

937
00:47:50,039 --> 00:47:51,973
Fresh air. I can't believe it.

938
00:47:52,041 --> 00:47:54,032
Even Communist air is better than no air.

939
00:47:54,110 --> 00:47:56,044
- Oh, uh...
- What?

940
00:47:56,112 --> 00:47:58,171
- You know, I, uh...
- You have everything?

941
00:47:58,247 --> 00:48:00,647
No, I don't know if I packed that thing.
You know, the...

942
00:48:00,716 --> 00:48:02,581
- The adaptor?
- Yeah, the adaptor.

943
00:48:02,651 --> 00:48:05,085
- You didn't take the adaptor?
- No, and it's Mildred's. I borrowed it.

944
00:48:05,154 --> 00:48:07,349
Mrs. Hollander, can I ask you
to wait inside one second?

945
00:48:07,423 --> 00:48:10,449
I know you're anxious but... Mr.
Hollander, you forgot something inside.

946
00:48:10,526 --> 00:48:13,154
- She forgot the adaptor.
- No, actually, we, uh...

947
00:48:13,229 --> 00:48:16,164
We have your passports,
Mr. Hollander. We have your passports.

948
00:48:16,232 --> 00:48:20,760
No, you're wrong because I got them from
Kilroy 'cause I knew you would forget.

949
00:48:20,836 --> 00:48:24,636
Please, Mr. Hollander. Just one second.
Did you sign our guest book?

950
00:48:24,707 --> 00:48:28,234
No, I'm never going back into that dump.
I've had it. I'm going home.

951
00:48:30,746 --> 00:48:32,680
<i>No, no, no, run!</i>

952
00:48:34,784 --> 00:48:37,378
Back! Get back! Get back!

953
00:48:40,623 --> 00:48:44,218
No, no, no, no, no! Up, up, up, up, up.

954
00:48:44,293 --> 00:48:46,227
I'm gonna blow your brains out if you move.

955
00:48:46,295 --> 00:48:48,525
- You're bluffing.
- I'm bluffing am I?

956
00:48:48,597 --> 00:48:50,531
Why don't you try calling it?

957
00:48:50,599 --> 00:48:53,466
You fool! That's a finger.

958
00:48:53,536 --> 00:48:56,562
It may look like a finger,
but it's a flesh-colored.45...

959
00:48:56,639 --> 00:49:00,473
- with two joints, a knuckle
and a little hair.

960
00:49:00,543 --> 00:49:04,673
They committed suicide!
The ones they were gonna trade us for.

961
00:49:04,747 --> 00:49:07,682
They had to do it...
This morning they had to pick to do it.

962
00:49:07,750 --> 00:49:10,412
<i>- Where do you want these?
- They couldn't wait till the weekend.</i>

963
00:49:10,486 --> 00:49:12,954
It's gonna be a beautiful weekend.
They could have gotten it all in.

964
00:49:13,022 --> 00:49:16,685
See? And you wanted to rush to work.

965
00:49:16,759 --> 00:49:18,693
I gotta call Barney Silverman.

966
00:49:18,761 --> 00:49:20,888
- I'm drowsy, Marion.
- You're drowsy?

967
00:49:20,963 --> 00:49:24,228
I took a Dramamine.
It's a half-hour before the flight.

968
00:49:24,300 --> 00:49:27,463
What are you lookin' at? I'm drowsy.

969
00:49:27,536 --> 00:49:31,131
I gotta get some coffee.

970
00:49:33,109 --> 00:49:35,134
Do you believe it? Here we are again.

971
00:49:47,756 --> 00:49:49,781
<i>There's something you should know. Uh...</i>

972
00:49:49,859 --> 00:49:53,158
I called Donald.
I told him the wedding's off.

973
00:49:53,229 --> 00:49:56,426
<i>You did?</i>

974
00:49:56,499 --> 00:50:00,560
- I'm not sure I heard that correctly.
- She's not marrying Donald!

975
00:50:02,404 --> 00:50:06,101
Don't make jokes with me,
because I can't take jokes, Marion.

976
00:50:06,175 --> 00:50:08,643
I was up all last night.
I didn't sleep a wink.

977
00:50:08,711 --> 00:50:12,078
The emir's aide sneezed on me. I have
camel germs coming out of everything.

978
00:50:12,148 --> 00:50:14,912
I'm not joking with you.
I'm not marrying Donald.

979
00:50:17,887 --> 00:50:21,584
<i>- Why not?
- Because she's not in love with him.</i>

980
00:50:21,657 --> 00:50:25,184
- What do you mean, you're not marrying Donald?
- I'm not in love with him.

981
00:50:25,261 --> 00:50:27,729
- What are you talking about?
- I'm not in love with him.

982
00:50:27,796 --> 00:50:31,493
- And I'm talking to her.
- So listen to her.

983
00:50:31,567 --> 00:50:34,035
What do you mean you're not?
How can you not marry him?

984
00:50:34,103 --> 00:50:36,765
I don't know.
Maybe I never was in love with him.

985
00:50:36,839 --> 00:50:40,070
What do you mean you weren't? The man
got her an expensive electric razor.

986
00:50:40,142 --> 00:50:42,110
- How could you not be in love with him?
- Dad, I'm mixed up.

987
00:50:42,178 --> 00:50:44,112
Don't confuse me more.

988
00:50:44,180 --> 00:50:46,410
You have to marry him.
You're in love with him.

989
00:50:46,482 --> 00:50:49,076
<i>No, Walter. You're in love with him.</i>

990
00:50:49,151 --> 00:50:51,881
I never said I wasn't. So what?

991
00:50:51,954 --> 00:50:55,515
If he was a female dermatologist,
you'd be sharing a flat in Paris.

992
00:50:55,591 --> 00:50:57,889
Oh! How can you do this?

993
00:50:57,960 --> 00:51:01,157
I don't know. I don't know.
He's not romantic enough.

994
00:51:01,230 --> 00:51:03,323
Since... I find him very romantic.

995
00:51:03,399 --> 00:51:06,459
- To you, not her.
- You're not the one he's holding in his arms.

996
00:51:06,535 --> 00:51:08,793
So if I let him hold me in
his arms, you'll marry him?

997
00:51:08,806 --> 00:51:09,561
No.

998
00:51:09,638 --> 00:51:12,630
Dad, no. It's over. Okay? It's over.

999
00:51:12,708 --> 00:51:14,835
Listen to her. What... How...

1000
00:51:14,910 --> 00:51:17,378
How is he not romantic?
The man is a derma...

1001
00:51:17,446 --> 00:51:19,971
What could be more romantic
than a dermatologist?

1002
00:51:20,049 --> 00:51:22,244
It's skin. He's a skin doctor.

1003
00:51:22,318 --> 00:51:24,843
The very words
of his profession are romantic.

1004
00:51:24,920 --> 00:51:27,445
Nevus. Rosacea.

1005
00:51:27,523 --> 00:51:30,617
Leukoplakia. It's like Hawaiian.
It evokes the tropics.

1006
00:51:30,693 --> 00:51:33,127
Walter, forget it.
Leave her alone. All right?

1007
00:51:33,195 --> 00:51:35,129
It's... You know...

1008
00:51:35,197 --> 00:51:39,327
This is our only daughter,
suddenly abandoned with child.

1009
00:51:39,401 --> 00:51:41,426
She's heavy with child...

1010
00:51:41,503 --> 00:51:43,994
I'm not with child!
What are you talking about?

1011
00:51:44,073 --> 00:51:46,405
What do you mean? You're not with child?

1012
00:51:46,475 --> 00:51:48,875
- I'm not with child.
- Since when are you not with child?

1013
00:51:48,944 --> 00:51:52,641
- She's never been with child.
- Where'd I get the impression she was with child?

1014
00:51:52,715 --> 00:51:55,775
I don't know. Maybe
you're thinking of your sister.

1015
00:51:55,851 --> 00:51:58,285
- My sister's with child?
- Yes, I told you. I was on the phone.

1016
00:51:58,354 --> 00:52:00,788
She told me. She's with child.

1017
00:52:00,856 --> 00:52:02,790
So we'll have to get her something.

1018
00:52:02,858 --> 00:52:05,224
I don't know what we're
going to get her around here.

1019
00:52:05,294 --> 00:52:07,558
- How do you get a baby gift...
- We'll get it at the duty free shop.

1020
00:52:07,630 --> 00:52:11,088
By the time we get to a duty free shop,
the kid's gonna be in college.

1021
00:52:11,166 --> 00:52:14,693
You should still marry Donald.
What's the difference? So you'll adopt.

1022
00:52:16,672 --> 00:52:21,041
I need you to clear up rumors
that all is not well at your embassy.

1023
00:52:21,110 --> 00:52:23,044
No, no, that's not true at all.

1024
00:52:23,112 --> 00:52:25,979
I heard there's been
some kind of a crisis...

1025
00:52:26,048 --> 00:52:29,506
where American spies have been
uncovered by the Reds?

1026
00:52:29,585 --> 00:52:32,748
If there's any spying being done,
it's being done on their side.

1027
00:52:32,821 --> 00:52:35,334
All goes very well there.
They're very happy there.

1028
00:52:35,347 --> 00:52:36,188
All righty.

1029
00:52:36,258 --> 00:52:38,192
If you'll excuse me, I'm in a hurry.

1030
00:52:38,260 --> 00:52:40,854
- Good to see you.
- Okay, thanks a lot. Bye-bye now.

1031
00:52:40,929 --> 00:52:43,159
Your Royal Highness, can you feel that?

1032
00:52:43,232 --> 00:52:45,462
- Can you move your toes?
- What are you doing?

1033
00:52:45,534 --> 00:52:48,025
- It's broken.
- Well, then, don't touch it. Don't move it!

1034
00:52:48,103 --> 00:52:51,266
- I won't. No, no, no.
- He shouldn't walk there. I just waxed!

1035
00:52:51,340 --> 00:52:53,274
Well, I wish you'd quit waxing everything.

1036
00:52:53,342 --> 00:52:55,276
I'm holding you responsible for this.

1037
00:52:55,344 --> 00:52:57,437
<i>The United States government
is extremely sorry about this.</i>

1038
00:52:57,513 --> 00:52:58,832
Sorry is not gonna help!

1039
00:52:58,845 --> 00:53:01,609
We have a very fine doctor
on staff from Bulgaria.

1040
00:53:01,684 --> 00:53:06,246
Well, uh, Dad, unfortunately
His Highness had a little accident.

1041
00:53:06,322 --> 00:53:10,383
No, it was nothing terrible.
He bro-broke his leg.

1042
00:53:12,561 --> 00:53:16,964
L-I don't know what to do. I ask her,
she just keeps waxing the floors.

1043
00:53:17,032 --> 00:53:19,899
Mr. Kilroy is now in full charge.

1044
00:53:19,968 --> 00:53:21,936
I want the Hollanders out of the embassy.

1045
00:53:22,004 --> 00:53:24,996
Do you understand, Axel? O-U-T, out!

1046
00:53:25,074 --> 00:53:28,066
Yesterday I had to dodge
embarrassing questions by Dean Rusk.

1047
00:53:28,143 --> 00:53:30,077
Someone even used the word "cover-up."

1048
00:53:30,145 --> 00:53:33,239
I will not have my life
sabotaged by a caterer.

1049
00:53:33,315 --> 00:53:36,216
<i>Well, sir, short of turning
them over to the Reds...</i>

1050
00:53:36,285 --> 00:53:38,219
I don't see a way out.

1051
00:53:38,287 --> 00:53:40,346
<i>I can't hear you.</i>

1052
00:53:40,422 --> 00:53:42,447
Axel...

1053
00:53:42,524 --> 00:53:46,688
there are certain tribes
that practice infanticide.

1054
00:53:46,762 --> 00:53:50,596
That is, if the child
is found to be defective...

1055
00:53:50,666 --> 00:53:52,600
the father has the right...

1056
00:53:52,668 --> 00:53:55,296
even the duty... to kill his son.

1057
00:53:55,371 --> 00:53:59,137
<i>Sir, I can't hear you. There's
some kind of a ruckus outside.</i>

1058
00:53:59,208 --> 00:54:01,540
<i>Um, can l... Can I call you back?</i>

1059
00:54:11,954 --> 00:54:15,651
All of a sudden, it's good-bye
successful dermatologist...

1060
00:54:15,724 --> 00:54:17,589
hello psychotic diplomat.

1061
00:54:17,659 --> 00:54:19,923
It's her own life, Walter. She's 21!

1062
00:54:19,995 --> 00:54:23,123
Marion, this guy is what we used
to call in the poolroom a "loser."

1063
00:54:23,198 --> 00:54:25,723
- He's a Harvard graduate!
- Because his father gives money.

1064
00:54:25,801 --> 00:54:29,635
- That's how he graduated. But he's a loser.
- Walter, don't get involved.

1065
00:54:29,705 --> 00:54:33,539
Of all her prospects over the years,
this is the single worst.

1066
00:54:33,609 --> 00:54:35,702
I prefer every one to him.

1067
00:54:35,778 --> 00:54:38,713
Even the draft dodger was better,
because he at least was a success.

1068
00:54:38,781 --> 00:54:40,715
He beat the draft. Something.

1069
00:54:40,783 --> 00:54:43,718
She was always a little lukewarm
about Donald, I felt.

1070
00:54:43,786 --> 00:54:47,745
<i>I didn't want to say anything, 'cause...</i>

1071
00:54:47,823 --> 00:54:50,053
<i>Hey, what are you doing with the stove?</i>

1072
00:54:50,125 --> 00:54:52,389
<i>Is this a stove?</i>

1073
00:54:52,461 --> 00:54:54,895
<i>It's a porcelain-tiled stove.</i>

1074
00:54:54,963 --> 00:54:57,397
<i>You think Europe has central heating?</i>

1075
00:54:57,466 --> 00:54:59,400
<i>I've been mailing letters in it.</i>

1076
00:54:59,468 --> 00:55:01,402
<i>Walter, come here.</i>

1077
00:55:01,470 --> 00:55:03,404
<i>Look what's going on!</i>

1078
00:55:03,472 --> 00:55:06,805
- Oh, Jesus, be careful.
- Rocks. They're throwing rocks!

1079
00:55:06,875 --> 00:55:08,968
Away from the window. Away. Down, down.

1080
00:55:09,044 --> 00:55:11,979
There was a small riot. If you
could please just go to your room.

1081
00:55:12,047 --> 00:55:14,140
- Quickly, go. Go.
- Aah. What do we do?

1082
00:55:14,216 --> 00:55:17,049
- Go to your room. Run!
- Try not to get shot.

1083
00:55:17,119 --> 00:55:21,453
Maybe you should go outside and address
them. You took a public speaking course.

1084
00:55:21,523 --> 00:55:24,822
<i>- Should have gone to Atlantic Beach.
- Oh, again with Atlantic Beach.</i>

1085
00:55:24,893 --> 00:55:28,693
All wives to the basement!
All wives, this way.

1086
00:55:32,167 --> 00:55:34,158
Get your valuables. Get all your valuables.

1087
00:55:34,236 --> 00:55:36,227
<i>I got 'em. Look at this!</i>

1088
00:55:36,305 --> 00:55:39,832
- Where's Susan?
- Get away from the windows.

1089
00:55:39,908 --> 00:55:43,071
- Get away from...
- Where's Susan?

1090
00:55:43,145 --> 00:55:43,773
<i>Oh, Susan!</i>

1091
00:55:43,786 --> 00:55:45,705
<i>Thank God. Kilroy got hit
in the head with a brick.</i>

1092
00:55:45,781 --> 00:55:49,376
- He's lying downstairs muttering something...
- God! Don't touch that.

1093
00:55:49,451 --> 00:55:51,385
It's an explosive!

1094
00:55:51,453 --> 00:55:53,387
- This is a bo...
- No, no. Don't put it down.

1095
00:55:53,455 --> 00:55:55,480
<i>- The slightest tap could blow us sky-high.</i>

1096
00:55:55,557 --> 00:55:57,491
My God, it's the emir!

1097
00:55:57,559 --> 00:56:01,154
<i>Your Majesty!</i>

1098
00:56:01,230 --> 00:56:03,164
Okay, let's get him in the basement.

1099
00:56:03,232 --> 00:56:05,166
Everybody, just stay calm.

1100
00:56:05,234 --> 00:56:08,795
Stay away from the windows. Everybody
stay low. Not you, Your Majesty.

1101
00:56:08,871 --> 00:56:10,839
- Walter, don't move! Hold on.
- Just stay still, okay?

1102
00:56:10,906 --> 00:56:13,841
I'm calm, I'm calm. Who's Walter?

1103
00:56:13,909 --> 00:56:17,845
<i>Move as quickly and as surely as...</i>

1104
00:56:17,913 --> 00:56:20,143
Oh, Your Majesty...

1105
00:56:20,215 --> 00:56:22,581
Try not to shake! If you shake,
it could make it go off...

1106
00:56:22,651 --> 00:56:25,381
- Just relax. Everybody relax.
- It's still ticking!

1107
00:56:25,454 --> 00:56:27,388
Are you sure you know what you're doing?

1108
00:56:27,456 --> 00:56:29,617
I'm a highly trained professional.

1109
00:56:29,691 --> 00:56:31,625
- Don't shake him!
- He's shaking.

1110
00:56:31,693 --> 00:56:34,389
- Just hold on to me. Okay, shh!
- Shh!

1111
00:56:34,463 --> 00:56:37,023
You're turning it the wrong way.
Get out of the room!

1112
00:56:37,099 --> 00:56:39,158
- Take her and go! Don't worry about me.
- What about you?

1113
00:56:39,234 --> 00:56:41,464
Look out the window, you'll see me
passing over the building.

1114
00:56:41,537 --> 00:56:43,471
We're not gonna leave you, Walter.

1115
00:56:43,539 --> 00:56:46,099
I can't cook with this going on.
A rock just landed in my chocolate...

1116
00:56:46,174 --> 00:56:48,802
<i>- It's not my fault.
- Don't you see what's going on here?</i>

1117
00:56:48,877 --> 00:56:52,278
<i>Don't move!</i>

1118
00:56:52,347 --> 00:56:55,248
- It's ticking. You have three seconds!
- Here we go, here we go.

1119
00:56:55,317 --> 00:56:57,512
- Ow!
- It's dead.

1120
00:56:58,854 --> 00:57:01,448
- My hair turned gray.
- Walter...

1121
00:57:01,523 --> 00:57:03,855
Marion, my bald spot is gray, I think.

1122
00:57:03,926 --> 00:57:08,761
Oh, Walter. Who tells you
to pick up strange objects?

1123
00:57:08,830 --> 00:57:10,821
- That's how we met.
- Ach.

1124
00:57:10,899 --> 00:57:14,995
- Has anyone been hurt?
- Uh, no, I think we're okay. How's everyone else?

1125
00:57:15,070 --> 00:57:17,766
Mr. Kilroy, downstairs, got
hit in the head with a brick.

1126
00:57:17,839 --> 00:57:20,330
He must have a concussion.
He thinks he's the Wright brothers.

1127
00:57:20,409 --> 00:57:23,469
The Wright brothers. Okay,
file a complaint with the ministry.

1128
00:57:23,545 --> 00:57:25,479
And you better call Washington.

1129
00:57:25,547 --> 00:57:27,777
No, no! Don't call Washington.
Just remain calm.

1130
00:57:27,849 --> 00:57:29,874
Just everybody remain calm.

1131
00:57:29,952 --> 00:57:32,648
- A bomb! I'm okay. I know the bomb.
- It was a bomb.

1132
00:57:32,721 --> 00:57:35,281
"Do what?" "Get that machine to fly."

1133
00:57:35,357 --> 00:57:37,791
- "Well, you're crazy." "Yes, but so are you."
- Mr. Burns!

1134
00:57:37,859 --> 00:57:40,760
<i>- Sir?
- You better get Mr. Kilroy to his room.</i>

1135
00:57:40,829 --> 00:57:42,763
- We may have to get him to a hospital.
- "What if something goes wrong?"

1136
00:57:42,831 --> 00:57:45,356
- You better get him twin beds.
- "Stop arguing."

1137
00:57:45,434 --> 00:57:47,425
<i>- Who here wants their laundry done?
- All right, okay.</i>

1138
00:57:47,502 --> 00:57:50,562
In the absence of any superiors,
I am now in charge of this embassy.

1139
00:57:50,639 --> 00:57:53,335
I'm in complete control of everything.

1140
00:57:53,408 --> 00:57:56,741
Good, now I feel safe, because
I heard him say he was in control.

1141
00:57:56,812 --> 00:57:59,110
- Go, better help the Russians.
- Axel?

1142
00:57:59,181 --> 00:58:00,042
Yeah.

1143
00:58:00,055 --> 00:58:02,673
They're not safe here.
That's what this is about.

1144
00:58:02,751 --> 00:58:05,652
- Mr. Kilroy? Mr. Kilroy?
- No! Wait, no.

1145
00:58:08,757 --> 00:58:13,558
Okay, nothing up my sleeve.
Right? One, two, three...

1146
00:58:13,629 --> 00:58:16,325
Here you...

1147
00:58:16,398 --> 00:58:18,764
- Is this good?
- What are you going to do with that?

1148
00:58:18,834 --> 00:58:20,927
- Just watch. Okay.
- L-I like this tie, Father.

1149
00:58:21,003 --> 00:58:23,904
Me, too. One of my favorites.

1150
00:58:23,972 --> 00:58:27,635
I place here a magic ladybug.

1151
00:58:27,709 --> 00:58:30,177
"Ladybug, ladybug, light as a feather...

1152
00:58:30,245 --> 00:58:32,907
make this tie all together."

1153
00:58:32,981 --> 00:58:35,415
So.

1154
00:58:35,484 --> 00:58:38,749
Okay. All right.

1155
00:58:44,860 --> 00:58:49,354
Okay. Okay... Oh, oh, oh, Mr. Magee!
One moment, please.

1156
00:58:49,431 --> 00:58:53,197
- Father, I'm a little busy right now...
- Very serious, please!

1157
00:58:53,268 --> 00:58:55,361
Okay.

1158
00:58:55,437 --> 00:58:57,701
- Okay.
- Father, what about my tie?

1159
00:58:57,773 --> 00:59:00,333
The reason this did not work
is because I'm still learning.

1160
00:59:00,409 --> 00:59:03,742
But God bless you.
God bless you, and good luck.

1161
00:59:03,812 --> 00:59:05,746
Okay.

1162
00:59:07,382 --> 00:59:11,113
<i>Our friends the Hollanders are in danger!</i>

1163
00:59:11,186 --> 00:59:13,586
That's what you came here to tell me,
Father? I'm aware of that.

1164
00:59:13,655 --> 00:59:16,283
No, no, no, no. Great danger.
I have information...

1165
00:59:16,358 --> 00:59:19,759
that the secret police intend
to kidnap them from this embassy.

1166
00:59:19,828 --> 00:59:21,762
Th-That's one thing
I'm not worried about...

1167
00:59:21,830 --> 00:59:24,492
because there are rules of
diplomatic protocol that preclude...

1168
00:59:24,566 --> 00:59:26,500
Please, you're dealing with the Communists.

1169
00:59:26,568 --> 00:59:28,763
They don't believe in God,
they eat too much fat...

1170
00:59:28,837 --> 00:59:30,805
and they, oh, share bathrooms.

1171
00:59:30,872 --> 00:59:32,806
We're trying everything.

1172
00:59:32,874 --> 00:59:35,240
Everything means nothing if
the Communists don't cooperate.

1173
00:59:35,310 --> 00:59:37,369
Mm-mm.

1174
00:59:37,446 --> 00:59:41,849
Listen. Listen to me.
I have decided. They must escape.

1175
00:59:41,917 --> 00:59:43,851
- Escape?
- Mm-hmm.

1176
00:59:43,919 --> 00:59:47,514
- All due respect, Father, but are you nuts?
- No, not nuts.

1177
00:59:47,589 --> 00:59:49,523
This is their only chance for survival.

1178
00:59:49,591 --> 00:59:52,583
No, we'll get more marines in here.
We'll pack the embassy.

1179
00:59:52,661 --> 00:59:54,788
For how long? For five years, ten years?

1180
00:59:54,863 --> 00:59:57,832
- Twelve years? Forget about it.
- Look, escape is not possible.

1181
00:59:57,899 --> 01:00:00,993
Uh, Houdini escaped.

1182
01:00:01,069 --> 01:00:04,197
This is not Houdini.
This is a man who carves...

1183
01:00:04,272 --> 01:00:06,206
bridegrooms out of potato salad.

1184
01:00:06,274 --> 01:00:09,334
Listen to me, I have information.
I have connections.

1185
01:00:09,411 --> 01:00:11,345
With the underground!

1186
01:00:11,413 --> 01:00:14,314
With loyal patriots who will
take them to safety, to America.

1187
01:00:14,382 --> 01:00:16,646
- Please!
- How are you gonna get them to America?

1188
01:00:16,718 --> 01:00:19,482
- We can't get 'em out of the embassy.
- Okay.

1189
01:00:19,554 --> 01:00:22,216
I will show you an example.
Give me one shoe.

1190
01:00:22,290 --> 01:00:24,588
- What?
- Give me one shoe!

1191
01:00:24,659 --> 01:00:26,593
- My shoe? No.
- Mm-hmm.

1192
01:00:26,661 --> 01:00:28,595
- Please!
- I'm not... No, I'm not gonna...

1193
01:00:28,663 --> 01:00:30,597
- A shoe. One shoe.
- Why do you need my shoe?

1194
01:00:30,665 --> 01:00:33,429
Give me one shoe!

1195
01:00:33,502 --> 01:00:35,493
This is...

1196
01:00:35,570 --> 01:00:38,164
- This is... I really don't have time for this.
- Thank you.

1197
01:00:38,240 --> 01:00:40,367
Please observe. Watch. Look.

1198
01:00:40,442 --> 01:00:42,876
Okay, I take one eggs.

1199
01:00:42,944 --> 01:00:45,936
I place the eggs inside the shoe.

1200
01:00:46,014 --> 01:00:50,075
Okay, now. I take the wand, and I place...

1201
01:00:53,722 --> 01:00:55,781
- Apprehensive?
- No, I'm not apprehensive, Father.

1202
01:00:55,857 --> 01:00:58,223
Because I saw the egg went up your sleeve.

1203
01:00:58,293 --> 01:01:01,091
Wrong. Listen to me. Look!

1204
01:01:01,163 --> 01:01:04,860
Okey-dokey. Misdirection.

1205
01:01:04,933 --> 01:01:08,460
And misdirection is how
we will get the Hollanders...

1206
01:01:08,537 --> 01:01:11,370
out of this embassy.

1207
01:01:11,439 --> 01:01:13,839
Understand?

1208
01:01:13,909 --> 01:01:16,139
Thank you.

1209
01:01:16,211 --> 01:01:19,374
Congratulations, it's a double yolk.

1210
01:01:19,447 --> 01:01:22,439
That's good luck! Oh!

1211
01:01:22,517 --> 01:01:24,246
<i>This is a good plan.</i>

1212
01:01:24,319 --> 01:01:26,947
<i>I can't agree. You'll all get killed!</i>

1213
01:01:27,022 --> 01:01:28,956
We'll get killed if we stay here!

1214
01:01:29,024 --> 01:01:31,424
I can't believe how much
I've screwed this up already.

1215
01:01:31,493 --> 01:01:35,156
<i>- You have not messed this up.
- My father's right. I'm a failure.</i>

1216
01:01:35,230 --> 01:01:37,164
And your father said it too.

1217
01:01:37,232 --> 01:01:40,793
And it's not just fathers. Lots of mothers
and brothers and sisters have said it.

1218
01:01:40,869 --> 01:01:41,773
Cousins, uncles...

1219
01:01:41,786 --> 01:01:44,532
First of all, you've got to
stop being so hard on yourself.

1220
01:01:44,606 --> 01:01:47,575
A lot of famous men had rough starts.
Hitler flunked out of art school.

1221
01:01:47,642 --> 01:01:49,735
- Thanks, Susan. That's very comforting.
- No, look.

1222
01:01:49,811 --> 01:01:53,645
- I see something wonderful in you.
- Your father can't do this!

1223
01:01:53,715 --> 01:01:56,309
<i>It's not pretty, a man with a hernia
being chased by a tank.</i>

1224
01:01:56,384 --> 01:01:58,318
<i>Will you forget my father for a minute?</i>

1225
01:01:58,386 --> 01:02:00,820
<i>If we never get out ofhere, how are
we going to have a future together?</i>

1226
01:02:00,889 --> 01:02:03,187
<i>- You don't want a future with me.
- How do you know?</i>

1227
01:02:03,258 --> 01:02:05,192
<i>It's not fun, the wife
of a career diplomat.</i>

1228
01:02:05,260 --> 01:02:08,058
Especially one who spends most of his life
in the unemployment insurance office.

1229
01:02:08,129 --> 01:02:12,065
We've got to tell my parents about this.
That's gonna be the hard part.

1230
01:02:12,133 --> 01:02:14,966
- Is it your turn?
- No, it's your turn. It's been ten minutes.

1231
01:02:15,036 --> 01:02:18,164
Mom, Dad, do you have a minute?
Axel has something he needs to tell you.

1232
01:02:18,240 --> 01:02:20,174
No more Donald. Now it's Axel.

1233
01:02:20,242 --> 01:02:22,767
She needs this hysteric
like a hole in the head.

1234
01:02:22,844 --> 01:02:28,407
- What does the failure have to tell us?
- Dad! Go ahead, darling.

1235
01:02:28,483 --> 01:02:31,543
Mr. Hollander, in light
of the circumstances...

1236
01:02:31,620 --> 01:02:33,611
and after much consideration...

1237
01:02:33,688 --> 01:02:36,350
well, I feel this situation
calls for drastic action.

1238
01:02:36,424 --> 01:02:39,552
The transplant guy was not
good enough? It has to be...

1239
01:02:39,628 --> 01:02:42,654
Let's just say, for purposes of
argument, that you were trapped spies.

1240
01:02:42,731 --> 01:02:43,909
What would you do?

1241
01:02:43,922 --> 01:02:47,430
I would deny it and claim
to be a caterer. Okay, happy?

1242
01:02:47,502 --> 01:02:50,562
- It's your turn!
- You've read the papers. What do families do...

1243
01:02:50,639 --> 01:02:52,664
when they're caught
behind the Berlin Wall...

1244
01:02:52,741 --> 01:02:57,440
and they desperately want freedom...
so desperately their lives depend on it?

1245
01:02:57,512 --> 01:02:59,980
What do they do? They escape.
They jump over the Wall.

1246
01:03:00,048 --> 01:03:03,017
They run through roadblocks.
They shoot. They forge pass...

1247
01:03:03,084 --> 01:03:05,279
Yeah.

1248
01:03:05,353 --> 01:03:08,948
Magee, it's been wonderful chatting
with you. Any other psychotic notions...

1249
01:03:09,024 --> 01:03:11,185
- We're playing dominoes.
- I'm afraid it's the only answer.

1250
01:03:11,259 --> 01:03:13,659
Escape? What an interesting idea.

1251
01:03:13,728 --> 01:03:16,959
What are you talking about? He's insane!

1252
01:03:17,032 --> 01:03:19,796
Years of insanity have made this guy crazy.

1253
01:03:19,868 --> 01:03:22,302
Dad, would you please just hear him out?
He's come into possession...

1254
01:03:22,370 --> 01:03:24,304
of some very alarming information.

1255
01:03:24,372 --> 01:03:27,466
- Did he get the results of his I.Q. Test back?
- We have reason to believe...

1256
01:03:27,542 --> 01:03:30,739
that the secret police are
planning to have you eliminated.

1257
01:03:30,812 --> 01:03:35,442
- Eliminated from what? We didn't enter anything.
- Walter, just hear him out!

1258
01:03:35,517 --> 01:03:38,816
Marion, I'm not an escaper.
It's not my style.

1259
01:03:38,887 --> 01:03:41,447
- I show up at a place and I stay.
- You can't stay.

1260
01:03:41,523 --> 01:03:44,424
- You're not safe here.
- But the priest is safe, right?

1261
01:03:44,492 --> 01:03:47,325
- Six years he's living upstairs...
- You wanna stay here for six years?

1262
01:03:47,395 --> 01:03:49,704
He's a relic of an old regime.
Krojack is different.

1263
01:03:49,717 --> 01:03:50,489
Dad, come on!

1264
01:03:50,565 --> 01:03:53,090
You can escape. You read about it
every day. Couples escape.

1265
01:03:53,168 --> 01:03:56,160
- A husband escapes. Lovers flee tyranny.
- What you read is...

1266
01:03:56,237 --> 01:04:00,264
"Husband Shot Escaping." "Couple Shot..."

1267
01:04:00,342 --> 01:04:02,276
What is she talking about?

1268
01:04:02,344 --> 01:04:05,507
You want her to stay here
for the rest of her life?

1269
01:04:05,580 --> 01:04:09,038
Yes, I'd rather she grew up here
than grow up an orphan.

1270
01:04:09,117 --> 01:04:12,018
I can tolerate anybody's orphans
but my own, okay?

1271
01:04:12,087 --> 01:04:14,351
- Walter, come here. Listen to me for a minute.
- I got a headache.

1272
01:04:14,422 --> 01:04:16,447
I got indigestion. I want to play dominoes.

1273
01:04:16,524 --> 01:04:19,186
Do you want your daughter
to see Donald again?

1274
01:04:19,260 --> 01:04:22,821
Or at least meet some other
eligible men? Don't you want that?

1275
01:04:25,200 --> 01:04:28,431
Tell me the plan. Just for fun.
Not that I'm interested...

1276
01:04:28,503 --> 01:04:30,596
but I want to know what he's thinking.

1277
01:04:30,672 --> 01:04:33,433
The night after tomorrow, we're
going to have a reception here.

1278
01:04:33,446 --> 01:04:34,369
Who's catering?

1279
01:04:34,442 --> 01:04:36,376
- Stop it!
- Would you let him finish?

1280
01:04:36,444 --> 01:04:39,971
It's a big party in honor of the emir.
Several hundred guests.

1281
01:04:40,048 --> 01:04:43,950
Dignitaries, men and women from
many nations, including this country.

1282
01:04:44,019 --> 01:04:47,113
Now, you two and Susan, get dressed.
You wait in your room.

1283
01:04:47,188 --> 01:04:47,776
Right.

1284
01:04:47,789 --> 01:04:49,588
Around midnight, when first
group of guests start to leave...

1285
01:04:49,657 --> 01:04:51,852
you come down, you put on your coats,
you got out with them.

1286
01:04:51,926 --> 01:04:52,705
Just like that.

1287
01:04:52,718 --> 01:04:55,089
Oh! It'll give you a chance
to wear your dark blue mohair.

1288
01:04:55,163 --> 01:04:57,461
I don't like my dark blue mohair.
My mohair itches.

1289
01:04:57,532 --> 01:05:00,160
How can mohair itch?
It's a very soft fabric.

1290
01:05:00,235 --> 01:05:02,965
- Sue me, it itches. I don't like the mohair.
- You're gonna have to wear...

1291
01:05:03,038 --> 01:05:06,064
a dark suit, because I'm not
gonna escape unless you dress.

1292
01:05:06,141 --> 01:05:08,473
I'm not dressing! We're not going anyplace.

1293
01:05:08,543 --> 01:05:10,977
The moment you go outside,
the embassy limousine will be waiting.

1294
01:05:11,046 --> 01:05:12,980
- You get in and you're off!
- It's simple.

1295
01:05:13,048 --> 01:05:15,846
- What if it works? Then where do we go?
- The rest is very simple.

1296
01:05:15,917 --> 01:05:20,149
My contacts are ready to see to it that
you'll be on your way home within hours.

1297
01:05:20,221 --> 01:05:24,783
Mr. Hollander, I implore you,
for the safety... of everyone involved.

1298
01:05:24,859 --> 01:05:27,623
We cannot procrastinate.
Timing is very important.

1299
01:05:27,695 --> 01:05:31,256
Walter, we'll get to see Seth again.
I miss him so much!

1300
01:05:31,332 --> 01:05:35,268
By the way, Walter, I didn't mention
this because I knew you'd get upset.

1301
01:05:35,336 --> 01:05:38,447
I got a letter from my brother.
Our apartment was robbed.

1302
01:05:38,460 --> 01:05:39,500
What?

1303
01:05:39,574 --> 01:05:40,802
Yes, burglars broke in.

1304
01:05:40,875 --> 01:05:44,072
They stole the portable TV
and all your custom-made shirts.

1305
01:05:44,145 --> 01:05:47,876
Oy, I'm a cursed caterer.
L-I'm running around here in Europe...

1306
01:05:47,949 --> 01:05:51,350
and in New York there's robbers
with my initials on their shirt.

1307
01:05:51,419 --> 01:05:53,353
- Evidently.
- Oy.

1308
01:05:53,421 --> 01:05:55,787
Can we, uh, start planning this?

1309
01:05:55,857 --> 01:06:00,817
Hello. Montague? This is Capulet.

1310
01:06:00,895 --> 01:06:02,829
Mmm.

1311
01:06:02,897 --> 01:06:07,561
The man with the blue scarf is in Vienna.

1312
01:06:07,635 --> 01:06:09,603
That's right.

1313
01:06:09,671 --> 01:06:13,903
The tulips are in full bloom.

1314
01:06:13,975 --> 01:06:18,742
Spring will be a little late this year.

1315
01:06:18,813 --> 01:06:22,579
And that's why the lady is a tramp.

1316
01:06:22,650 --> 01:06:24,880
<i>Over and in.</i>

1317
01:06:30,825 --> 01:06:34,625
There is a reception
for a Middle Eastern dignitary.

1318
01:06:34,696 --> 01:06:37,392
I and my wife have been invited.

1319
01:06:37,465 --> 01:06:39,933
I thought you'd be interested in knowing.

1320
01:06:41,236 --> 01:06:44,831
<i>R-Right.</i>

1321
01:06:44,906 --> 01:06:47,170
Of course, you will attend.

1322
01:06:47,242 --> 01:06:50,905
<i>- I'll see to it that you're briefed in detail.
- Absolutely. Of course.</i>

1323
01:06:50,979 --> 01:06:54,608
<i>- Comrade Luchow will take your wife's place.
- Oh?</i>

1324
01:06:54,682 --> 01:06:57,810
Naturally, you will
introduce her as "Anna."

1325
01:06:58,987 --> 01:07:01,854
Understood. Understood.

1326
01:07:01,923 --> 01:07:05,120
There's something...

1327
01:07:05,193 --> 01:07:08,492
There's something going on there.

1328
01:07:08,563 --> 01:07:11,657
This ambassador's son, the young Magee.

1329
01:07:11,733 --> 01:07:14,361
He's either a genius...

1330
01:07:14,435 --> 01:07:16,369
or an idiot.

1331
01:07:25,213 --> 01:07:26,441
Look, tonight's the night.

1332
01:07:26,514 --> 01:07:29,244
I'd just feel better if we
go over the whole thing again.

1333
01:07:29,317 --> 01:07:31,615
It's a rotten plan, it won't work.
Let's call it off.

1334
01:07:31,686 --> 01:07:34,382
- We're not calling anything off.
- Hi, Mr. Hollander. Who are you?

1335
01:07:34,455 --> 01:07:36,514
Who am I? Who am I. I'm-I'm...

1336
