Or fluid, or flints.

1552
01:18:47,461 --> 01:18:50,555
- Oh, no. No matter.
- This works on a different principle, right?

1553
01:18:50,631 --> 01:18:52,758
- Haven't figured it out yet.
- Well, we have to be going.

1554
01:18:52,833 --> 01:18:55,563
Party's about over, and I hate to be
the last to leave.

1555
01:18:55,636 --> 01:18:58,230
- Yes, well, nice meeting you.
- It was a pleasure.

1556
01:18:58,305 --> 01:19:00,899
- Lucky those cheap lighters never work.
- I don't want to hear...

1557
01:19:00,975 --> 01:19:03,205
- Can we go now, please?
- Yes, yes.

1558
01:19:03,277 --> 01:19:07,077
- I don't believe we've had the pleasure.
- Sam Randall.

1559
01:19:07,147 --> 01:19:10,241
- John. John Randall.
- John Randall, from...

1560
01:19:10,317 --> 01:19:13,343
I'm Helmut Gruber, and this is
my lovely wife, Mrs. Gruber.

1561
01:19:13,420 --> 01:19:16,548
Hi. How do you do?

1562
01:19:16,624 --> 01:19:19,593
We weren't aware there were
other American guests here.

1563
01:19:19,660 --> 01:19:21,787
- No, there aren't.
- I'd like to freshen up.

1564
01:19:21,862 --> 01:19:24,729
- Have you met the Hollanders?
- The Hollanders? No!

1565
01:19:24,798 --> 01:19:26,857
- We don't know the Hollanders.
- Pick a card.

1566
01:19:26,934 --> 01:19:28,993
- Any card.
- No, no, no. Not now, Drobney.

1567
01:19:29,069 --> 01:19:31,003
- Oh, please. Pick a card.
- No, no, no.

1568
01:19:31,071 --> 01:19:33,005
Yes, yes, yes. Go pick.

1569
01:19:33,073 --> 01:19:36,338
Picking. More picking. Please pick a card.

1570
01:19:36,410 --> 01:19:39,004
- It's got writing on it. Plus, we've got...
- Nah!

1571
01:19:39,079 --> 01:19:42,242
<i>- Walter, it's so late, we should...
- Randall!</i>

1572
01:19:42,316 --> 01:19:45,547
Mr. Randall. Mister, uh, your car.

1573
01:19:45,619 --> 01:19:47,553
- Yes, the car.
- Good evening.

1574
01:19:48,822 --> 01:19:50,756
Mm.

1575
01:19:50,824 --> 01:19:54,260
<i>...tie it together again.
- He's a priest. Magic is not his full-time job.</i>

1576
01:19:54,328 --> 01:19:58,264
- I have to go. I'm sorry.
- But he said he was gonna put it together.

1577
01:19:58,332 --> 01:20:02,200
- Well, Mr. Magee, thank you so much.
- Very nice party.

1578
01:20:02,269 --> 01:20:05,261
- Thank you very much.
- A lovely, lovely evening.

1579
01:20:05,339 --> 01:20:08,331
- Very, very nice party. Here.
- Yes, we'll be going.

1580
01:20:08,409 --> 01:20:11,503
- Oh, yes. Nice to have chatted with you.
- Come on, Carmen.

1581
01:20:11,578 --> 01:20:15,139
Hope to see you soon.
Yes, John, yes. Good-bye.

1582
01:20:15,215 --> 01:20:17,115
<i>Yes, well, um...</i>

1583
01:20:17,184 --> 01:20:19,311
- Nice to meet you.
- Nice to have met you.

1584
01:20:19,386 --> 01:20:21,650
And maybe, maybe I'll see you
in Newark sometime.

1585
01:20:21,722 --> 01:20:23,883
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

1586
01:20:31,198 --> 01:20:33,996
"Orville, do you think they'll give us
a parade up Fifth Avenue?"

1587
01:20:34,068 --> 01:20:38,801
"I don't doubt it." "Mother would love
that." "She would, wouldn't she?"

1588
01:20:38,872 --> 01:20:41,306
<i>Oh, my God!</i>

1589
01:20:41,375 --> 01:20:44,572
What happened? Oh, my goodness,
what happened?

1590
01:20:44,645 --> 01:20:48,479
Oh, what happened? Oh, my...

1591
01:20:51,218 --> 01:20:55,120
Stay calm! That's right. Oh, my God!

1592
01:20:55,189 --> 01:20:57,419
Tell me what the hell happened?

1593
01:20:59,660 --> 01:21:02,322
- Who shot me?
- Whoa.

1594
01:21:02,396 --> 01:21:04,330
Dad.

1595
01:21:07,134 --> 01:21:08,624
<i>No, I will not hear of it.</i>

1596
01:21:08,702 --> 01:21:11,603
<i>Send the embassy limousines.
We leave immediately.</i>

1597
01:21:11,672 --> 01:21:13,640
His Majesty will not stay an extra minute.

1598
01:21:13,707 --> 01:21:16,938
<i>- But, sir, l...
- No, now, now! This instant!</i>

1599
01:21:17,011 --> 01:21:19,411
- Oscar has prepared a wonderful brunch.
- No. Brunch?

1600
01:21:19,480 --> 01:21:23,507
- I am not going to stay here for brunch.
- Let me get the ambassador.

1601
01:21:23,584 --> 01:21:27,850
How could you do that?
How could you attempt an escape?

1602
01:21:27,921 --> 01:21:31,084
Dad, the situation called
for something bold, you know?

1603
01:21:31,158 --> 01:21:33,126
- If it had worked...
- But it failed!

1604
01:21:33,193 --> 01:21:35,127
Like everything else you do, it failed!

1605
01:21:35,195 --> 01:21:39,188
I mean, riots, bombs, pickets,
that's never happened in my embassy.

1606
01:21:39,266 --> 01:21:41,200
And this morning
a devout priest produced...

1607
01:21:41,268 --> 01:21:43,634
a seven of spades behind my left ear.

1608
01:21:43,704 --> 01:21:47,868
<i>- He's been working on that.
- He was having a hard time...</i>

1609
01:21:47,941 --> 01:21:50,375
- Come in!
- "The flight went well."

1610
01:21:50,444 --> 01:21:53,311
<i>- Flight?
- "Yes, it did, Orville. I was surprised."</i>

1611
01:21:53,380 --> 01:21:55,405
"Me too, Wilbur."

1612
01:21:55,482 --> 01:21:58,007
"Well, I shouldn't say
surprised, but encouraged."

1613
01:21:58,085 --> 01:22:02,454
"Me too." "Now, you mark my words,
we'll show the world."

1614
01:22:02,523 --> 01:22:07,119
I'll get you for this, Axel.
I promise you, I will get you for this.

1615
01:22:07,194 --> 01:22:10,357
<i>The emir's leaving.
I think the situation is irreparable.</i>

1616
01:22:10,431 --> 01:22:15,562
<i>I'll speak to him. By the way,
your mother called.</i>

1617
01:22:15,636 --> 01:22:18,434
She wants you to mail her
your birth certificate.

1618
01:22:18,505 --> 01:22:21,201
- Come on, boys.
- Huh? Oh. "Have you met my brother?"

1619
01:22:21,275 --> 01:22:23,470
"Oh, hello. You look very well."

1620
01:22:23,544 --> 01:22:26,069
"Thank you, I feel well."

1621
01:22:27,948 --> 01:22:33,011
Well, you wondered what happens,
you go along with a lunatic.

1622
01:22:33,087 --> 01:22:36,022
I told you the gun was dangerous.

1623
01:22:36,090 --> 01:22:38,024
Again, she's still on the gun.

1624
01:22:38,092 --> 01:22:41,528
You shot two people in the last
24 hours! How many do you need?

1625
01:22:41,595 --> 01:22:45,326
Marion, how am I gonna know
there was the ambassador?

1626
01:22:45,399 --> 01:22:49,062
- You want him to wear a little sign?
- The gun went off by itself!

1627
01:22:49,136 --> 01:22:52,264
I didn't shoot the gun. It must have
been one of those new guns.

1628
01:22:52,339 --> 01:22:55,968
They buy 'em by the bushel from Taiwan.

1629
01:22:56,043 --> 01:22:59,206
Axel, I'm sorry. This was all our fault.
Right, Dad?

1630
01:22:59,279 --> 01:23:01,213
If it was anybody's fault, it was my fault.

1631
01:23:01,281 --> 01:23:03,249
And now they've doubled the guards outside.

1632
01:23:03,317 --> 01:23:06,514
It was a nice try, Magee.
Unfortunately, I shot the boss.

1633
01:23:06,587 --> 01:23:08,646
But you know, you can't have everything.

1634
01:23:08,722 --> 01:23:12,055
I better call Barney Silverman.
He's probably still at Montauk Point...

1635
01:23:12,126 --> 01:23:15,220
with the station wagon,
waiting for us to surface.

1636
01:23:15,295 --> 01:23:18,025
- What is this? What are you doing?
- Just doing a little laundry.

1637
01:23:18,098 --> 01:23:20,328
Mr. Burns says the emir is packing.

1638
01:23:20,400 --> 01:23:24,131
- She's doing laundry.
- She does Kilroy, she does Burns...

1639
01:23:24,204 --> 01:23:27,298
she dusts, she waxes, and now
she's doing the bedouins.

1640
01:23:27,374 --> 01:23:29,308
Just two of his wives.

1641
01:23:29,376 --> 01:23:33,278
They're lovely young women.
I'll give it to them.

1642
01:23:33,347 --> 01:23:35,542
- Wait a minute. Wait a minute.
- What's the matter?

1643
01:23:35,616 --> 01:23:37,880
<i>- I got an idea.
- I heard that. He's got an idea.</i>

1644
01:23:37,951 --> 01:23:40,181
- I'll be in the fallout shelter.
- How many do you have?

1645
01:23:40,254 --> 01:23:42,347
- Just two.
- Okay.

1646
01:23:42,422 --> 01:23:45,516
- What are you thinking?
- Father Drobney, come down here.

1647
01:23:45,592 --> 01:23:48,584
What's going through your mind, Magee,
besides the usual cattle stampede?

1648
01:23:48,662 --> 01:23:51,028
Stand right there. Yeah, it'll fit.

1649
01:23:51,098 --> 01:23:53,623
- Wait, this could work. Do you see?
- We gotta hurry, though.

1650
01:23:53,700 --> 01:23:56,897
- They're gonna leave any minute.
- What are we discussing?

1651
01:23:56,970 --> 01:23:59,598
- You know I'm a size ten.
- Yeah. Okay, you two.

1652
01:23:59,673 --> 01:24:01,607
- Change. Quickly.
- Change what?

1653
01:24:01,675 --> 01:24:04,235
- I don't get it.
- We leave with the emir's harem!

1654
01:24:04,311 --> 01:24:06,279
What's wrong with you?

1655
01:24:06,346 --> 01:24:08,439
- A harem?
- Yes.

1656
01:24:08,515 --> 01:24:12,349
- The two of us...
- Yeah, because with the veils, wh-who'll notice?

1657
01:24:12,419 --> 01:24:14,478
He has 14, now he's got two more.

1658
01:24:14,555 --> 01:24:16,523
You're telling me the man
doesn't count his harem?

1659
01:24:16,590 --> 01:24:19,753
- Who doesn't count the harem?
- This is a brilliant plan! This could work.

1660
01:24:19,826 --> 01:24:22,795
- No, no, no, no, no. I'm not dressing as an Arab.
- No, no, you are.

1661
01:24:22,863 --> 01:24:25,730
And then you get into the embassy limousine,
it takes you to the transfer point...

1662
01:24:25,799 --> 01:24:27,994
and you meet Drobney's contacts!

1663
01:24:28,068 --> 01:24:31,902
- Instantly he can see there's two more wives.
- Maybe he will, maybe he won't.

1664
01:24:31,972 --> 01:24:34,099
- It's worth a shot.
- Don't tell me maybe. I don't want to know maybe.

1665
01:24:34,174 --> 01:24:37,405
Forget it. Let him spend the money
on a lobotomy.

1666
01:24:37,477 --> 01:24:40,674
- We're wasting time here.
- What about Susan? We only have two outfits.

1667
01:24:40,747 --> 01:24:43,409
I got that figured out too.

1668
01:24:43,483 --> 01:24:46,247
- You two, just dress, okay?
- All right. Let's go.

1669
01:24:46,320 --> 01:24:49,187
- Walter, here.
- I'm not dressing, Marion. Leave me alone.

1670
01:24:49,256 --> 01:24:51,724
I don't want to wind up in a harem.
We'll spend the rest of our lives...

1671
01:24:51,792 --> 01:24:54,090
on satin pillows in the Persian Gulf.

1672
01:24:54,161 --> 01:24:57,528
- Quickly. Would you change?
- No, I don't want to.

1673
01:24:57,598 --> 01:24:59,896
Marion, is that what you want?
To be a love slave?

1674
01:24:59,967 --> 01:25:03,095
You're at least a man. I'm the one that's
gonna have to learn those wiggly dances.

1675
01:25:03,170 --> 01:25:05,229
<i>- Let's go!
- How did you think of this?</i>

1676
01:25:05,305 --> 01:25:07,603
- I never would have thought of this plan.
- Ah...

1677
01:25:07,674 --> 01:25:11,166
So sorry. Cold compresses.
Wives. Clear. Coming through.

1678
01:25:11,245 --> 01:25:13,213
Mr. Magee. You called?

1679
01:25:13,280 --> 01:25:15,341
Father Drobney. Are your
contacts still ready to go?

1680
01:25:15,354 --> 01:25:16,044
Yes.

1681
01:25:16,116 --> 01:25:18,050
- Good. Alert them immediately.
- Absolutely.

1682
01:25:18,118 --> 01:25:19,121
All systems go.

1683
01:25:19,134 --> 01:25:22,179
You're transforming before my eyes.
It's wonderful.

1684
01:25:22,256 --> 01:25:24,190
Susan, every once in a while
fate comes along...

1685
01:25:24,258 --> 01:25:26,453
takes a man by the hand and
allows him to move mountains.

1686
01:25:26,526 --> 01:25:28,721
- Isn't it faith? I think it's faith.
- Is it... faith?

1687
01:25:28,795 --> 01:25:31,787
I always thought it was fate.
Maybe that's why it never made sense.

1688
01:25:31,865 --> 01:25:35,232
- I'm so proud of you.
- Before you walked into my life...

1689
01:25:35,302 --> 01:25:38,760
- I was nothing, I was a loser...
- I didn't walk into your life.

1690
01:25:38,839 --> 01:25:39,760
I ran.

1691
01:25:39,773 --> 01:25:42,570
But now, I have this
feeling I could do anything!

1692
01:25:42,643 --> 01:25:45,874
I have this confidence,
this sense of optimism.

1693
01:25:45,946 --> 01:25:48,574
Maybe you're really a manic-depressive.

1694
01:25:48,649 --> 01:25:51,584
- No, I'm in love.
- You're in love.

1695
01:25:51,652 --> 01:25:54,951
I'm in love, for the first time
since Elsie Holmquist.

1696
01:25:55,022 --> 01:25:57,081
- Who's Elsie Holmquist? You never mentioned her.
- This Swedish girl.

1697
01:25:57,157 --> 01:25:59,352
I met her in an embassy.
Boy, could she ski.

1698
01:25:59,426 --> 01:26:02,361
- That's how I broke my pelvis.
- Oh.

1699
01:26:02,429 --> 01:26:05,057
- Susan, you've become my whole world.
- You've become mine.

1700
01:26:05,132 --> 01:26:07,464
I am so happy, I could sing!

1701
01:26:07,534 --> 01:26:10,002
Do I have to listen to this?

1702
01:26:10,070 --> 01:26:12,971
- Ha! Okay.
- See you in a minute.

1703
01:26:13,040 --> 01:26:16,373
The storm we were expecting
will be a little late.

1704
01:26:16,443 --> 01:26:19,037
The boy with the blue hair...

1705
01:26:19,112 --> 01:26:21,740
is fondling his chipmunk.

1706
01:26:21,815 --> 01:26:25,376
<i>Never call with anything under...</i>

1707
01:26:25,452 --> 01:26:27,682
a pair of queens.

1708
01:26:27,754 --> 01:26:31,019
And the green grass grows all around.

1709
01:26:31,091 --> 01:26:33,116
All around.

1710
01:26:33,193 --> 01:26:36,162
So, toot, toot, tootsie, good-bye.

1711
01:26:36,229 --> 01:26:38,254
<i>Ready.</i>

1712
01:26:38,332 --> 01:26:41,130
- Marion, it itches.
- How can it itch? This is silk.

1713
01:26:41,201 --> 01:26:45,137
I'm telling you a million times. My doctor
told me I have the thighs of a princess.

1714
01:26:45,205 --> 01:26:47,673
- So you wearing a princess's clothes.
- It itches!

1715
01:26:47,741 --> 01:26:49,709
- It's silk.
- Everything is ready.

1716
01:26:49,776 --> 01:26:51,710
Go immediately and God bless you.

1717
01:26:51,778 --> 01:26:55,475
Just stay calm, cool, collected,
and if anybody asks you anything...

1718
01:26:55,549 --> 01:26:57,483
just mutter something about Allah.

1719
01:26:57,551 --> 01:26:58,170
Uh-huh.

1720
01:26:58,183 --> 01:27:00,076
The limousine driver will
take you to the Grand Hotel.

1721
01:27:00,153 --> 01:27:02,644
From there on, our plans
are precisely the same.

1722
01:27:02,723 --> 01:27:05,851
- What about Susan? We didn't decide.
- In a little while...

1723
01:27:05,926 --> 01:27:09,327
Susan and I are gonna walk out of here
under full diplomatic immunity.

1724
01:27:09,396 --> 01:27:12,490
- How are we gonna do that?
- Well, as the wife of a foreign diplomat...

1725
01:27:12,566 --> 01:27:14,500
you'd be entitled to that.

1726
01:27:14,568 --> 01:27:17,298
- Wife? You-You and her?
- It's perfect.

1727
01:27:17,371 --> 01:27:20,932
We're both American citizens.
This is United States territory.

1728
01:27:21,007 --> 01:27:23,305
Father Drobney is a priest.

1729
01:27:23,377 --> 01:27:26,813
- If you'll have me.
- Oh, Axel!

1730
01:27:26,880 --> 01:27:30,316
My Susan! A bride!

1731
01:27:30,384 --> 01:27:33,751
This is the happiest day of my life!

1732
01:27:33,820 --> 01:27:37,278
I only wish your father
were alive to see this!

1733
01:27:37,357 --> 01:27:40,326
- I am alive. I'm standing right here.
- Oh, yeah.

1734
01:27:40,394 --> 01:27:43,522
- I'm sorry! I got carried away.
- 'Cause I'm wearing this.

1735
01:27:43,597 --> 01:27:47,089
- You look like you should be named Fatima.
- This is a brilliant plan.

1736
01:27:47,167 --> 01:27:50,625
- You're gonna marry her? She's gonna marry...
- Yes!

1737
01:27:50,704 --> 01:27:53,468
- You want him to?
- I do, yes! I love you.

1738
01:27:53,540 --> 01:27:57,704
Oh. Oh! Oh.

1739
01:27:57,778 --> 01:28:00,542
Walter. Walter. Stop that. We have to go.

1740
01:28:00,614 --> 01:28:02,878
Walter. Walter, control yourself.

1741
01:28:02,949 --> 01:28:04,883
- Mr. Hollander...
- Stop! Stop!

1742
01:28:04,951 --> 01:28:06,885
All right. Shh! Walter.

1743
01:28:06,953 --> 01:28:09,353
Listen, Susan. Darling.

1744
01:28:09,423 --> 01:28:11,857
When we're on the submarine,
you'll wire me your silverware pattern.

1745
01:28:11,925 --> 01:28:14,894
- Absolutely. As soon as I know.
- Good luck.

1746
01:28:14,961 --> 01:28:16,826
- You stepped on my Hush Puppies!
- Oh, sorry.

1747
01:28:16,897 --> 01:28:21,834
- Walter, take it easy.
- Let's go.

1748
01:28:21,902 --> 01:28:24,200
Now, now!

1749
01:28:24,271 --> 01:28:27,263
- But they're marrying!
- Yes!

1750
01:28:27,340 --> 01:28:31,743
God keep them. I'm so happy for you both.

1751
01:28:31,812 --> 01:28:34,280
- Thank you.
- I'm happy. Are you happy?

1752
01:28:34,347 --> 01:28:37,339
- Yeah!
- I'm happy.

1753
01:28:37,417 --> 01:28:39,408
You look so great.

1754
01:28:39,486 --> 01:28:42,717
Father, I didn't speak out of turn.
You can do a ceremony, right?

1755
01:28:42,789 --> 01:28:45,724
- Yes, I could do. Yes. Six years I haven't.
- Is he a rabbi?

1756
01:28:45,792 --> 01:28:47,726
- Do we need a rabbi?
- Hour and a half...

1757
01:28:47,794 --> 01:28:50,285
<i>- Do you know any rabbis in the underground?
- Just have to change my clothes.</i>

1758
01:28:54,568 --> 01:28:57,935
Come. Come, let's go. Soon
we will be home at the palace...

1759
01:28:58,004 --> 01:29:00,529
and I expect every one of you
to go out of your way...

1760
01:29:00,607 --> 01:29:05,237
to see that His Majesty forgets
this unpleasant occurrence.

1761
01:29:05,312 --> 01:29:08,645
I'm sure you know what I mean, hmm?

1762
01:29:08,715 --> 01:29:12,151
- Hey, why is he staring at me?
- You look sexy in those clothes.

1763
01:29:12,219 --> 01:29:16,212
I don't like this, Marion.
I don't like this.

1764
01:29:16,289 --> 01:29:18,849
Well, you look fine.

1765
01:29:22,729 --> 01:29:25,789
<i>That morning, the Hollanders
left the United States embassy...</i>

1766
01:29:25,866 --> 01:29:29,825
<i>with a boldness and courage
unknown to them before.</i>

1767
01:29:29,903 --> 01:29:34,101
<i>Indeed, the plan devised by Axel Magee
was a brilliant one.</i>

1768
01:29:34,174 --> 01:29:37,234
<i>The following day, they
were married by Father Drobney.</i>

1769
01:29:37,310 --> 01:29:42,077
Therefore, I pronounce you man and wife.

1770
01:29:42,148 --> 01:29:45,174
Congratulations!

1771
01:29:49,389 --> 01:29:53,189
Look. Hey! Oh, it's a joke.

1772
01:29:53,260 --> 01:29:57,993
<i>Within 24 hours, the Hollanders were
safely en route to the United States.</i>

1773
01:29:58,064 --> 01:30:00,794
<i>Axel Magee quit the Foreign Service...</i>

1774
01:30:00,867 --> 01:30:03,131
<i>and went to work for his father-in-law...</i>

1775
01:30:03,203 --> 01:30:06,434
<i>who was overwhelmed with
the young man's natural gifts...</i>

1776
01:30:06,506 --> 01:30:09,600
<i>for sculpting the bride and groom
out of chopped liver.</i>

1777
01:30:09,676 --> 01:30:14,238
<i>At last, the fortune-teller's prediction
about Magee as a new Michelangelo...</i>

1778
01:30:14,314 --> 01:30:16,339
<i>had proved true.</i>

